1
00:00:00,410 --> 00:00:05,259
CHAPTER ONE
Creativity

2
00:00:05,259 --> 00:00:13,650
On a cool fall evening in 2008, four students
decided to change an industry. They were all

3
00:00:13,650 --> 00:00:20,820
deep in debt, and they had all lost or broken
their glasses. They were shocked at how much

4
00:00:20,820 --> 00:00:26,960
it would cost to replace them. One of them
had been wearing the same pair of broken,

5
00:00:26,960 --> 00:00:34,250
and repaired, glasses for five years. He refused
to pay for an expensive new pair.

6
00:00:34,250 --> 00:00:40,640
Luxottica, the biggest company in the glasses
industry, controlled more than 80 percent

7
00:00:40,640 --> 00:00:48,920
of the market. To make glasses cheaper, the
four students would need to fight a giant.

8
00:00:48,920 --> 00:00:55,510
The four had watched Zappos change the shoe
market by selling shoes online, and they wondered

9
00:00:55,510 --> 00:00:59,020
if they could do the same with glasses.

10
00:00:59,020 --> 00:01:05,770
They discussed the idea with friends, most
of whom were very negative. Nobody would buy

11
00:01:05,770 --> 00:01:13,860
glasses over the internet, they said. People
needed to try them first. OK, Zappos had done

12
00:01:13,860 --> 00:01:20,430
it with shoes, but there were reasons why
it wouldn't work with glasses. "If this were

13
00:01:20,430 --> 00:01:24,430
a good idea," people said, "someone would
have done it already."

14
00:01:24,430 --> 00:01:32,810
None of the students had worked in internet
sales or technology, and they knew nothing

15
00:01:32,810 --> 00:01:41,580
about glasses or fashion. But they agreed
to start a company. They decided to sell glasses

16
00:01:41,580 --> 00:01:49,560
that would cost 500 dollars in stores for
95 dollars online, and they would also give

17
00:01:49,560 --> 00:01:55,450
another pair of glasses to someone in the
poorer countries in the developing world for

18
00:01:55,450 --> 00:02:03,940
each pair that they sold. They called their
company Warby Parker.

19
00:02:03,940 --> 00:02:09,720
The most important part of the business would
be its website, and their Warby Parker website

20
00:02:09,720 --> 00:02:18,230
was ready in February 2010. They expected
to sell one or two pairs of glasses a day,

21
00:02:18,230 --> 00:02:26,390
but in less than one month, they had 20,000
customers on a waiting list.

22
00:02:26,390 --> 00:02:34,650
In 2015, the magazine Fast Company published
its yearly list of the world's most innovative

23
00:02:34,650 --> 00:02:42,480
companies. Warby Parker was the first company
on that list. In the three previous years,

24
00:02:42,480 --> 00:02:51,430
the winners had been Google, Nike, and Apple
- companies with over 50,000 employees. Warby

25
00:02:51,430 --> 00:02:59,150
Parker had just 500 employees, but in five
years, the company had given more than 1 million

26
00:02:59,150 --> 00:03:06,490
free pairs of glasses to the developing world.
The company was making 100 dollars million

27
00:03:06,490 --> 00:03:11,990
a year and was worth more than 1 billion dollars.

28
00:03:11,990 --> 00:03:22,210
Back in 2009, one of those four students asked
me to invest in Warby Parker. I refused. It

29
00:03:22,210 --> 00:03:28,510
was the worst financial decision I have ever
made. I needed to understand where I went

30
00:03:28,510 --> 00:03:32,730
wrong.

31
00:03:32,730 --> 00:03:36,650
Conformity and originality

32
00:03:36,650 --> 00:03:46,430
Years ago, psychologists discovered that there
are two roads to success: conformity and originality.

33
00:03:46,430 --> 00:03:52,599
Conformity means following the crowds down
the usual paths. Originality means taking

34
00:03:52,599 --> 00:03:59,290
unusual roads and developing new ideas that
are accepted only by a few people, but that

35
00:03:59,290 --> 00:04:02,240
succeed in the end.

36
00:04:02,240 --> 00:04:08,120
Of course, nothing is completely original:
our ideas are affected by the world around

37
00:04:08,120 --> 00:04:18,000
us. We all borrow thoughts, sometimes by accident,
sometimes not. What I mean here by "originality"

38
00:04:18,000 --> 00:04:24,680
is introducing and advancing an idea that
is quite unusual in a particular area, and

39
00:04:24,680 --> 00:04:28,980
may improve that area.

40
00:04:28,980 --> 00:04:36,230
Originality begins with creativity: having
an idea that is both new and useful. But it

41
00:04:36,230 --> 00:04:45,000
doesn't stop there. Originals are people who
can make their new idea really work. The Warby

42
00:04:45,000 --> 00:04:51,620
Parker people had the originality to think
of selling glasses online, but they became

43
00:04:51,620 --> 00:04:58,910
originals by taking action to make those glasses
cheap and easy to buy.

44
00:04:58,910 --> 00:05:05,930
This book is about how we can all become more
original. There's a surprising clue in the

45
00:05:05,930 --> 00:05:11,600
web browser that you use to search the internet.

46
00:05:11,600 --> 00:05:15,310
The problem with defaults

47
00:05:15,310 --> 00:05:21,270
In a recent research project, Michael Housman
was investigating why some people who worked

48
00:05:21,270 --> 00:05:28,590
in customer call centers for big companies
stayed in their jobs longer than others. He

49
00:05:28,590 --> 00:05:35,660
collected information on 30,000 employees
who answered phones for banks, airlines, and

50
00:05:35,660 --> 00:05:41,560
cell phone companies. He expected to find
that their employment histories would give

51
00:05:41,560 --> 00:05:48,230
him an answer. He thought people who had changed
jobs often in the past would leave their present

52
00:05:48,230 --> 00:05:53,780
jobs more quickly. But that wasn't true.

53
00:05:53,780 --> 00:05:59,660
Looking at his research, Housman noticed that
his team had collected information about the

54
00:05:59,660 --> 00:06:05,650
internet browser that the employees had used
when they applied for their job. He didn't

55
00:06:05,650 --> 00:06:12,680
think he would find anything interesting there,
but the results were amazing. Employees who

56
00:06:12,680 --> 00:06:20,120
used Firefox or Chrome stayed in their jobs
15 percent longer than those who used Internet

57
00:06:20,120 --> 00:06:23,820
Explorer or Safari.

58
00:06:23,820 --> 00:06:31,310
Housman thought this was strange, so then
he looked at absences from work. Again, Firefox

59
00:06:31,310 --> 00:06:38,820
and Chrome users were 19 percent less likely
to miss work than Internet Explorer and Safari

60
00:06:38,820 --> 00:06:41,250
users.

61
00:06:41,250 --> 00:06:47,720
Then Housman looked at how employees performed
in their jobs. The Firefox and Chrome users

62
00:06:47,720 --> 00:06:56,340
had higher sales, and their call times were
shorter. Their customers were happier, too.

63
00:06:56,340 --> 00:07:01,880
Housman knew it wasn't the web browser that
made these people good employees. What made

64
00:07:01,880 --> 00:07:09,680
the difference was how they had gotten their
browsers. If you buy a PC, Internet Explorer

65
00:07:09,680 --> 00:07:17,570
is built into Windows. If you buy a Mac, it
comes with Safari. But if you choose to use

66
00:07:17,570 --> 00:07:22,130
Firefox or Chrome, you are not accepting the
default.

67
00:07:22,130 --> 00:07:28,540
It's the same at work. The people who didn't
accept the default for their browser did their

68
00:07:28,540 --> 00:07:35,400
jobs differently. They didn't always accept
the usual answers, and they helped their customers

69
00:07:35,400 --> 00:07:38,699
with new ideas.

70
00:07:38,699 --> 00:07:45,460
Accepting the default is easy, but it doesn't
ask us to look at new ways of doing things.

71
00:07:45,460 --> 00:07:52,479
Before the four people behind Warby Parker
started to think about their company, they

72
00:07:52,479 --> 00:08:00,021
knew glasses were expensive, but that had
always been true. That was the default; everybody

73
00:08:00,021 --> 00:08:06,320
thought there was a good reason why glasses
were expensive. After all, these are health

74
00:08:06,320 --> 00:08:09,180
products: a doctor is selling them.

75
00:08:09,180 --> 00:08:18,580
Then, Dave Gilboa, one of the four, was buying
an Apple iPhone. Why was this phone, a piece

76
00:08:18,580 --> 00:08:26,060
of modern technology, cheaper than a simple
pair of glasses? Warby Parker decided to look

77
00:08:26,060 --> 00:08:32,519
at the glasses industry more closely. One
company, Luxottica, was the biggest in the

78
00:08:32,519 --> 00:08:41,269
market. Simply, Luxottica could charge what
it wanted: twenty times the cost of the glasses.

79
00:08:41,269 --> 00:08:49,870
And this meant that a different company could
do things very differently.

80
00:08:49,870 --> 00:08:52,819
Accepting defaults

81
00:08:52,819 --> 00:09:00,179
We begin to accept defaults when we are very
young. When researchers interviewed schoolteachers,

82
00:09:00,179 --> 00:09:06,139
they asked them to list their favorite and
least favorite students. They then asked the

83
00:09:06,139 --> 00:09:14,879
teachers which students had the most creativity,
and these were often the least favorite students.

84
00:09:14,879 --> 00:09:20,279
Teachers found that the creative students
often made trouble, while most children learned

85
00:09:20,279 --> 00:09:24,230
to do what the teacher wanted.

86
00:09:24,230 --> 00:09:29,160
You might think it is the most intelligent
children who change the world when they become

87
00:09:29,160 --> 00:09:36,790
adults. But that doesn't often happen. They
may become excellent doctors, but they don't

88
00:09:36,790 --> 00:09:42,920
ask why some people cannot afford healthcare.
They may become lawyers who defend people

89
00:09:42,920 --> 00:09:50,120
against unfair laws, but they don't question
the laws themselves. They may become teachers

90
00:09:50,120 --> 00:09:58,480
who teach exciting lessons but without asking,
what their students really need to learn.

91
00:09:58,480 --> 00:10:05,029
The problem for many intelligent children
is that we expect them to achieve. It becomes

92
00:10:05,029 --> 00:10:11,730
so important for them to achieve that they
start to fear failure, which can hold back

93
00:10:11,730 --> 00:10:14,019
creativity.

94
00:10:14,019 --> 00:10:20,421
Fear of failure held back some of the most
original people in history, people who, instead

95
00:10:20,421 --> 00:10:27,589
of pushing ahead with confidence, held themselves
back through fear of failure. They only took

96
00:10:27,589 --> 00:10:33,389
action because other people persuaded them
to do so.

97
00:10:33,389 --> 00:10:40,230
The men who signed the American Declaration
of Independence were not natural revolutionaries.

98
00:10:40,230 --> 00:10:46,230
George Washington just wanted to go back to
his farm and only became involved because

99
00:10:46,230 --> 00:10:54,050
John Adams asked him to command the army.
"I have used everything in my power to avoid

100
00:10:54,050 --> 00:10:59,870
it," Washington wrote in a letter to his wife,
Martha, in 1766.

101
00:10:59,870 --> 00:11:07,110
Two hundred years later, Martin Luther King,
Jr. wanted to work in the church and as a

102
00:11:07,110 --> 00:11:14,509
teacher. But, when Rosa Parks refused to give
up her seat on a bus to a white man, some

103
00:11:14,509 --> 00:11:22,360
people in Montgomery, Alabama, decided to
organize a group to support her. At a meeting,

104
00:11:22,360 --> 00:11:28,880
someone suggested King as president of the
group. King didn't have time to think, and

105
00:11:28,880 --> 00:11:36,079
he accepted. He said afterward that, if he
had had time to think, he would probably have

106
00:11:36,079 --> 00:11:38,889
refused.

107
00:11:38,889 --> 00:11:43,949
When the Church asked Michelangelo to paint
the ceiling of the Sistine Chapel in Rome,

108
00:11:43,949 --> 00:11:51,559
he wasn't interested. He didn't want to take
on such a huge job and ran away to Florence.

109
00:11:51,559 --> 00:11:59,519
But he was asked again and again, and after
two years he agreed to start work.

110
00:11:59,519 --> 00:12:10,009
Nearly 500 years later, in 1977, an investor
offered Steve Jobs and Steve Wozniak 250,000

111
00:12:10,009 --> 00:12:17,489
dollars to help them start Apple. But the
investor demanded that Wozniak leave his job

112
00:12:17,489 --> 00:12:24,629
at Hewlett- Packard. Wozniak was afraid to
leave his job, and he only agreed when he

113
00:12:24,629 --> 00:12:31,399
was encouraged by Steve Jobs, other friends,
and his parents.

114
00:12:31,399 --> 00:12:39,089
We can only wonder how many Kings, Michelangelos,
and Wozniaks had original ideas but were never

115
00:12:39,089 --> 00:12:46,470
pushed to develop them. Many of us have ideas
to improve our workplaces or schools, but

116
00:12:46,470 --> 00:12:53,309
we don't give voice to them. Originality can
get you into trouble, and most of us prefer

117
00:12:53,309 --> 00:12:56,389
to conform.

118
00:12:56,389 --> 00:13:01,720
What are the habits of people who are original,
and who take action to develop their original

119
00:13:01,720 --> 00:13:05,620
ideas?

120
00:13:05,620 --> 00:13:07,079
How to be an entrepreneur

121
00:13:07,079 --> 00:13:17,519
To be an original you need to take big risks.
That's what most people think. We admire astronauts

122
00:13:17,519 --> 00:13:24,579
like Neil Armstrong and Sally Ride, who left
the only planet we know and went bravely into

123
00:13:24,579 --> 00:13:32,059
space. We admire leaders like Mahatma Gandhi
and Martin Luther King, Jr., who risked their

124
00:13:32,059 --> 00:13:38,529
lives for the things they believed in. And
we admire entrepreneurs like Steve Jobs and

125
00:13:38,529 --> 00:13:44,660
Bill Gates, who dropped out of school and
worked in dark garages to develop the products

126
00:13:44,660 --> 00:13:47,579
of the future.

127
00:13:47,579 --> 00:13:54,220
The word "entrepreneur" was created by Richard
Cantillon, and it means someone who takes

128
00:13:54,220 --> 00:14:01,319
risks. When we read about the rise of Warby
Parker, we see the four friends who started

129
00:14:01,319 --> 00:14:08,639
the company as great risk-takers. But is it
true?

130
00:14:08,639 --> 00:14:15,309
Six months before Warby Parker started business,
Neil Blumenthal, one of the four friends,

131
00:14:15,309 --> 00:14:22,000
was one of my students. He came to see me
because he wanted me to invest in their company.

132
00:14:22,000 --> 00:14:28,379
I told him that it was an interesting idea,
but I wasn't sure that people would buy glasses

133
00:14:28,379 --> 00:14:35,100
online. As it would be difficult to persuade
people to buy online, I felt it would need

134
00:14:35,100 --> 00:14:41,689
an enormous amount of work to get the company
going. And, when I discovered what Neil and

135
00:14:41,689 --> 00:14:47,989
his friends were planning to do with their
own lives, I was even less sure.

136
00:14:47,989 --> 00:14:54,320
The first problem was that Neil and his friends
were still in school. If they believed in

137
00:14:54,320 --> 00:14:59,839
Warby Parker, they should all drop out and
work full time on Warby Parker.

138
00:14:59,839 --> 00:15:07,040
"No," said Neil. "We're not sure it's a good
idea, and we don't know if we will succeed.

139
00:15:07,040 --> 00:15:10,259
We're working on it in our spare time."

140
00:15:10,259 --> 00:15:17,079
However, they were all finishing school at
the end of the year. So after that they could

141
00:15:17,079 --> 00:15:19,779
work full time on the project.

142
00:15:19,779 --> 00:15:26,309
"No," said Neil. "If things don't work out,
I'm taking a full-time job after I finish

143
00:15:26,309 --> 00:15:30,149
school. And so are the others."

144
00:15:30,149 --> 00:15:38,829
That was enough for me. I decided not to invest.
The Warby Parker friends did not fit my picture

145
00:15:38,829 --> 00:15:46,100
of successful entrepreneurs. They weren't
prepared to risk everything on one idea. I

146
00:15:46,100 --> 00:15:52,559
thought they were going to fail because they
didn't want any risk. But, in fact, that is

147
00:15:52,559 --> 00:15:56,609
why they succeeded.

148
00:15:56,609 --> 00:16:04,119
In an interesting piece of research, Joseph
Raffiee and Jie Feng studied 5,000 entrepreneurs

149
00:16:04,119 --> 00:16:11,970
over fourteen years. They wanted the answer
to one simple question. When people start

150
00:16:11,970 --> 00:16:19,679
a business, is it better for them to leave
their present job, or to stay employed?

151
00:16:19,679 --> 00:16:24,880
If you think like most people, you would expect
the risk-takers who leave their jobs to be

152
00:16:24,880 --> 00:16:32,369
more successful. But the opposite happens.
Entrepreneurs who keep their original jobs

153
00:16:32,369 --> 00:16:40,959
are 33 percent less likely to fail than the
risk-takers who leave their jobs.

154
00:16:40,959 --> 00:16:45,609
If you don't like to take risks, and have
some doubts about your business, you will

155
00:16:45,609 --> 00:16:51,720
build your business more carefully. If you
take risks in your life, then you may take

156
00:16:51,720 --> 00:16:56,139
risks with your business, too.

157
00:16:56,139 --> 00:17:01,730
Like Warby Parker, many successful businesses
were started by people who did not give up

158
00:17:01,730 --> 00:17:09,241
their jobs - at least at the beginning. After
inventing the first Apple I computer, Steve

159
00:17:09,241 --> 00:17:17,370
Wozniak started Apple with Steve Jobs in 1976
but continued to work for Hewlett- Packard

160
00:17:17,370 --> 00:17:26,829
until 1977. Larry Page and Sergey Brin developed
a better way to search the internet in 1996

161
00:17:26,829 --> 00:17:34,260
but didn't stop work on their higher degrees
at Stanford University until 1998. They tried

162
00:17:34,260 --> 00:17:41,380
to sell Google for less than 2 million dollar
in 1997 because their new company was making

163
00:17:41,380 --> 00:17:48,300
it difficult to study -luckily, nobody made
an offer.

164
00:17:48,300 --> 00:17:55,430
Brian May was doing a higher degree in physics
when he started to play guitar in a new band.

165
00:17:55,430 --> 00:18:03,030
He continued to study for several years before
he started to play full time for Queen. Stephen

166
00:18:03,030 --> 00:18:10,400
King worked in a gas station and as a teacher
for seven years after writing his first story.

167
00:18:10,400 --> 00:18:18,500
He finally gave up work a year after his first
novel, Carrie, was published.

168
00:18:18,500 --> 00:18:25,640
These people were all balancing their risk:
taking a big risk in one part of their lives

169
00:18:25,640 --> 00:18:34,400
but playing safe with another. Keeping things
safe meant that there was space to be original.

170
00:18:34,400 --> 00:18:40,150
And because the entrepreneurs were not taking
such a big financial risk there was more time

171
00:18:40,150 --> 00:18:46,030
available: there was less danger of starting
the business with a poor-quality product in

172
00:18:46,030 --> 00:18:53,290
an effort to get the money back quickly. As
Malcolm Gladwell wrote in the New Yorker,

173
00:18:53,290 --> 00:19:00,500
"Many entrepreneurs take plenty of risks - but
those are generally the failed entrepreneurs,

174
00:19:00,500 --> 00:19:05,320
not the success stories."

175
00:19:05,320 --> 00:19:09,320
From idea to action

176
00:19:09,320 --> 00:19:15,640
Having revealed that successful originals
often begin by questioning defaults and balancing

177
00:19:15,640 --> 00:19:23,560
risk, the rest of this book is about moving
from original ideas to action. I have spent

178
00:19:23,560 --> 00:19:29,920
more than ten years researching originality
and studying some of the most successful originals

179
00:19:29,920 --> 00:19:37,830
of our time. I want to share with you how
we can all be more original, without taking

180
00:19:37,830 --> 00:19:44,940
too many risks with our personal, financial,
and professional lives. I hope that what I

181
00:19:44,940 --> 00:19:50,780
have discovered will help people develop their
originality and will help leaders develop

182
00:19:50,780 --> 00:19:55,290
originality in their organizations.

183
00:19:55,290 --> 00:20:01,560
The first part of this book looks at how to
manage the risks in developing, recognizing,

184
00:20:01,560 --> 00:20:09,850
and pushing forward original ideas. New ideas
are risky, and we need to learn how to recognize

185
00:20:09,850 --> 00:20:18,510
good ideas and avoid the bad ones. Once you
are sure that you have a good idea, the next

186
00:20:18,510 --> 00:20:25,080
step is to get other people to understand
it. You'll discover how the most popular television

187
00:20:25,080 --> 00:20:31,910
show ever nearly didn't get made, and why
an entrepreneur told investors the reasons

188
00:20:31,910 --> 00:20:36,680
why they shouldn't invest in his company.

189
00:20:36,680 --> 00:20:42,150
The second part of this book looks at the
choices we need to make when developing original

190
00:20:42,150 --> 00:20:49,220
ideas. There are the risks of being first
to the market: it's sometimes riskier to move

191
00:20:49,220 --> 00:20:56,540
early than it is to be late. Delaying can
help entrepreneurs build businesses that are

192
00:20:56,540 --> 00:21:04,500
stronger over time, and it can help originals
remain creative. I will also look at building

193
00:21:04,500 --> 00:21:11,330
coalitions of people to work together, and
how sometimes it can be useful to work with

194
00:21:11,330 --> 00:21:14,440
your enemies.

195
00:21:14,440 --> 00:21:20,550
The third part of this book looks at how to
develop originality in children and explains

196
00:21:20,550 --> 00:21:28,530
how our family, and others, make us more or
less likely to question defaults. You'll see

197
00:21:28,530 --> 00:21:34,170
how whether or not baseball players are the
first child in a family affects the risks

198
00:21:34,170 --> 00:21:40,770
that they take. I'll also look at how leaders
can encourage the development of creative

199
00:21:40,770 --> 00:21:43,290
ideas in their companies.

200
00:21:43,290 --> 00:21:51,510
To finish, I'll look at what stops us from
developing our originality. The originals

201
00:21:51,510 --> 00:21:58,030
are the people who push us all forward. On
the inside, they are not that different from

202
00:21:58,030 --> 00:22:04,880
the rest of us. They have the same fears and
doubts. What makes them different is that

203
00:22:04,880 --> 00:22:13,050
they try, even though they have fears and
doubts. They know failure is a smaller disappointment

204
00:22:13,050 --> 00:22:18,120
than failing to try.

205
00:22:18,120 --> 00:22:24,210
CHAPTER TWO
Ideas and inventors

206
00:22:24,210 --> 00:22:32,460
Around the year 2000, a lot of people in Silicon
Valley were very interested in a new invention.

207
00:22:32,460 --> 00:22:39,380
Steve Jobs said it was the most exciting technology
since the computer. He offered the inventor

208
00:22:39,380 --> 00:22:48,450
63 million dollars to buy 10 percent of the
company, but the inventor wasn't interested.

209
00:22:48,450 --> 00:22:55,970
The man behind Amazon, Jeff Bezos, told the
inventor, "You have a product so revolutionary,

210
00:22:55,970 --> 00:22:59,500
you'll have no problem selling it."

211
00:22:59,500 --> 00:23:05,320
The inventor was described as a modern Thomas
Edison, and he was behind a number of exciting

212
00:23:05,320 --> 00:23:13,130
medical inventions. He thought his new invention
would have sales of 10,000 a week in its first

213
00:23:13,130 --> 00:23:21,300
year. But, after six years, he had only sold
30,000, and the company still wasn't making

214
00:23:21,300 --> 00:23:29,710
money. The invention was expected to change
lives and cities around the world, but today

215
00:23:29,710 --> 00:23:34,960
it is only used in a few special markets.

216
00:23:34,960 --> 00:23:43,300
The revolutionary product was the Segway - a
machine with two wheels that carries you around.

217
00:23:43,300 --> 00:23:51,050
Why did so many people think it was going
to be a success? Why did they get it wrong?

218
00:23:51,050 --> 00:23:58,120
A few years earlier, two writers wrote a 90-minute
television program. They had never written

219
00:23:58,120 --> 00:24:04,530
for television before, and they soon found
they didn't have enough material for 90 minutes,

220
00:24:04,530 --> 00:24:11,510
so they decided to write a weekly half-hour
show. But when they sent their work to a television

221
00:24:11,510 --> 00:24:17,930
company the people there either didn't like
it, or didn't understand it.

222
00:24:17,930 --> 00:24:26,630
One program was made and shown to a test audience
of 100 people. The viewers didn't like it.

223
00:24:26,630 --> 00:24:34,740
600 more people in four different cities watched
it. The report on those test audiences said:

224
00:24:34,740 --> 00:24:39,630
"Nobody in the audience wanted to watch the
show again."

225
00:24:39,630 --> 00:24:49,010
Surprisingly, the program did make it to television,
and, as expected, it wasn't successful. But

226
00:24:49,010 --> 00:24:54,460
one person at the television company believed
in it and argued that they should try making

227
00:24:54,460 --> 00:25:03,550
some more shows. These were made, and shown
a year later, and, again, they weren't popular.

228
00:25:03,550 --> 00:25:09,600
The television company were going to cancel
the program but agreed to do a few more shows

229
00:25:09,600 --> 00:25:16,200
when another program was canceled. One of
the writers almost left the show - he had

230
00:25:16,200 --> 00:25:19,600
no more ideas.

231
00:25:19,600 --> 00:25:25,700
It's a good thing he changed his mind. For
the next ten years, the program was one of

232
00:25:25,700 --> 00:25:33,880
the most popular on television, and it made
more than 1 billion dollars. TV Guide named

233
00:25:33,880 --> 00:25:40,800
it the greatest television program of all
time. Why did the television companies not

234
00:25:40,800 --> 00:25:45,460
believe in Seinfeld?

235
00:25:45,460 --> 00:25:50,610
When we say there is not enough originality
in the world we think it is because there

236
00:25:50,610 --> 00:25:57,670
is not enough creativity. We think that if
only people had more new ideas we would be

237
00:25:57,670 --> 00:26:07,510
better off. But the real problem is not new
ideas - it's selecting the right ideas. Our

238
00:26:07,510 --> 00:26:13,650
companies and countries have many people with
new ideas. What they don't have are people

239
00:26:13,650 --> 00:26:21,410
who can choose the right new ideas. Segway
was a false positive: people thought it would

240
00:26:21,410 --> 00:26:29,500
be a success, but it wasn't. Seinfeld was
a false negative: people expected it to fail,

241
00:26:29,500 --> 00:26:32,570
but it succeeded.

242
00:26:32,570 --> 00:26:39,640
This chapter is about selecting the right
ideas. We'll look at two people who did expect

243
00:26:39,640 --> 00:26:45,810
the Segway to fail, and at the one person
in the television company who believed in

244
00:26:45,810 --> 00:26:52,690
Seinfeld. We'll see how these people made
the right decisions, and how we can become

245
00:26:52,690 --> 00:26:58,750
better at choosing the right ideas.

246
00:26:58,750 --> 00:27:02,010
Judging creativity

247
00:27:02,010 --> 00:27:08,760
The inventor of the Segway was a brilliant
man called Dean Kamen. He had started inventing

248
00:27:08,760 --> 00:27:17,280
when he was sixteen, and some of his inventions
were very successful. In the 1990s, he designed

249
00:27:17,280 --> 00:27:25,400
the iBOT, a wheelchair that could climb stairs.
He realized that the technology of the iBOT

250
00:27:25,400 --> 00:27:33,070
could be used more widely, and he put together
a team to design the Segway. He wanted something

251
00:27:33,070 --> 00:27:39,280
that would be safe, friendly for the environment,
and would help people to move around busy

252
00:27:39,280 --> 00:27:47,280
cities. Because it was small, light, and easy
to ride, it would be great for mail carriers,

253
00:27:47,280 --> 00:27:55,420
police officers, and golfers, but it could
also change the way everybody traveled. The

254
00:27:55,420 --> 00:28:01,641
Segway was the most amazing technology he
had ever created. Kamen thought it would,

255
00:28:01,641 --> 00:28:08,460
replace the car, in the same way that the
car had replaced the horse.

256
00:28:08,460 --> 00:28:15,220
But inventors are not the best people to judge
their own inventions. Studies show that most

257
00:28:15,220 --> 00:28:20,160
of us are bad at judging ourselves. For example:

258
00:28:20,160 --> 00:28:27,720
: 70 percent of high school seniors think
they are "above average" leaders; 2 percent

259
00:28:27,720 --> 00:28:29,030
think they are below average

260
00:28:29,030 --> 00:28:35,870
: 94 percent of college professors think their
work is above average

261
00:28:35,870 --> 00:28:45,680
: in two different companies, 32 percent and
42 percent of engineers estimated they were

262
00:28:45,680 --> 00:28:50,340
in the top 5 percent in their work.

263
00:28:50,340 --> 00:28:57,750
When we have developed an idea, we are usually
too close to it to judge it accurately. In

264
00:28:57,750 --> 00:29:04,370
music, many experts think Beethoven was a
good critic of his own music. But Beethoven's

265
00:29:04,370 --> 00:29:12,230
own favorite pieces have not been the ones
played most. Aaron Kozbelt looked at letters

266
00:29:12,230 --> 00:29:18,260
where Beethoven judged seventy of his works
and compared Beethoven's estimates with those

267
00:29:18,260 --> 00:29:26,419
of other experts. Of those seventy works,
Beethoven estimated fifteen false positives

268
00:29:26,419 --> 00:29:33,530
- works that he thought were important, but
that are not - and eight false negatives - works

269
00:29:33,530 --> 00:29:41,059
that he thought unsuccessful, but that are
now judged very highly. That's 33 percent

270
00:29:41,059 --> 00:29:47,210
wrong, even though Beethoven was judging his
work after audiences had heard and judged

271
00:29:47,210 --> 00:29:50,710
it.

272
00:29:50,710 --> 00:29:53,910
Kissing frogs

273
00:29:53,910 --> 00:30:00,650
If originals are not good at judging their
own work, how do they create great products?

274
00:30:00,650 --> 00:30:08,280
They have a lot of ideas. Dean Simonton has
looked at many really successful creators

275
00:30:08,280 --> 00:30:14,770
and discovered that they didn't have better
ideas than others; they had more. By producing

276
00:30:14,770 --> 00:30:20,410
more ideas, they had a better chance of originality.

277
00:30:20,410 --> 00:30:28,420
Think about William Shakespeare. In twenty
years, he wrote thirty-seven plays and 154

278
00:30:28,420 --> 00:30:35,270
poems. In order to judge how popular they
were, Simonton looked at how often the plays

279
00:30:35,270 --> 00:30:43,380
were performed. Three of Shakespeare's five
most popular plays, Macbeth, King Lear, and

280
00:30:43,380 --> 00:30:48,860
Othello, were written in the same five years
that he wrote Timon of Athens and All's Well

281
00:30:48,860 --> 00:30:55,180
That Ends Well, which many people feel are
among the worst of his plays.

282
00:30:55,180 --> 00:31:03,800
Pablo Picasso produced more than 1,800 paintings,
12,000 drawings, and thousands of other works,

283
00:31:03,800 --> 00:31:12,350
but only a small number of these are widely
admired. Albert Einstein published 248 papers

284
00:31:12,350 --> 00:31:20,520
over his life, but most of them are not considered
important. We know Maya Angelou's poem "Still

285
00:31:20,520 --> 00:31:27,120
I Rise" and her book I Know Why the Caged
Bird Sings, but we forget about her other

286
00:31:27,120 --> 00:31:36,020
165 poems and six books. If you want to be
original, "the most important possible thing

287
00:31:36,020 --> 00:31:43,650
you could do," says Ira Glass, "is do a lot
of work."

288
00:31:43,650 --> 00:31:49,060
Many people think that if you want to do better
work you should do less and spend time on

289
00:31:49,060 --> 00:31:58,900
delivering high-quality work. But having a
lot of ideas is the best way to get to quality.

290
00:31:58,900 --> 00:32:04,559
Original thinkers will have many ideas that
are of no use, but, because they develop so

291
00:32:04,559 --> 00:32:11,560
many ideas, it is more likely some of them
will be successful.

292
00:32:11,560 --> 00:32:17,970
When he was developing the Segway, Dean Kamen
knew it was important to explore as many ideas

293
00:32:17,970 --> 00:32:25,250
as possible. "You've got to kiss a lot of
frogs," he would say to his team, "before

294
00:32:25,250 --> 00:32:32,380
you find a prince." He encouraged them to
look at hundreds of different ways of solving

295
00:32:32,380 --> 00:32:40,020
the problems they met. The problem was that
he decided to develop the Segway without knowing

296
00:32:40,020 --> 00:32:46,460
whether, in the end, it would be a frog or
a prince.

297
00:32:46,460 --> 00:32:52,930
One of the best ways of judging our ideas
is to get feedback. One of the writers of

298
00:32:52,930 --> 00:32:59,610
The Daily Show, Lizz Winstead, still doesn't
know, after years of working on the comedy

299
00:32:59,610 --> 00:33:06,660
program, what will make people laugh. In the
past, she would try jokes out on stage, to

300
00:33:06,660 --> 00:33:14,309
an audience. Some jokes made people laugh,
some didn't. Now, with social media she can

301
00:33:14,309 --> 00:33:21,270
get feedback more quickly. When she thinks
of a joke, she shares it on Twitter. When

302
00:33:21,270 --> 00:33:28,059
she has something longer to share, she uses
Facebook. At the end of the day, the feedback

303
00:33:28,059 --> 00:33:33,330
tells her whether an idea is worth developing
or not.

304
00:33:33,330 --> 00:33:39,580
When developing the Segway, Dean Kamen didn't
look for feedback. He was afraid that somebody

305
00:33:39,580 --> 00:33:47,960
would steal his idea, so he kept the program
secret. Many of his own employees weren't

306
00:33:47,960 --> 00:33:54,590
allowed to see the Segway while it was being
developed. So the team working on the Segway

307
00:33:54,590 --> 00:34:01,510
developed a huge number of ideas, but they
didn't get any feedback from customers. No

308
00:34:01,510 --> 00:34:05,840
customers saw it when it was being developed.

309
00:34:05,840 --> 00:34:12,399
But Kamen and his team weren't the only people
who were enthusiastic about the Segway. Why

310
00:34:12,399 --> 00:34:19,909
did Steve Jobs and Jeff Bezos make the same
mistake? To find the answer to that question,

311
00:34:19,909 --> 00:34:25,559
let's first look at why so many people were
wrong about Seinfeld.

312
00:34:25,559 --> 00:34:31,269
The danger of false negatives

313
00:34:31,269 --> 00:34:36,339
When the television company first looked at
Seinfeld, they didn't know what to do with

314
00:34:36,339 --> 00:34:42,929
it. It wasn't like other television programs.
They didn't want to take a risk on something

315
00:34:42,929 --> 00:34:51,509
new like this. It would be better to develop
a safe idea than take a risk on this new one.

316
00:34:51,509 --> 00:34:56,529
This way of thinking produces false negatives.

317
00:34:56,529 --> 00:35:02,799
The false negative is something that happens
often in the media. Film companies rejected

318
00:35:02,799 --> 00:35:10,790
movies like Star Wars, E. T, and Pulp Fiction.
Publishers refused books like The Diary of

319
00:35:10,790 --> 00:35:19,420
Anne Frank, Gone with the Wind, and Harry
Potter - by 2015, J. K. Rowling's Harry Potter

320
00:35:19,420 --> 00:35:26,800
books had brought in over 25 billion dollars
and sold more copies than any book series

321
00:35:26,800 --> 00:35:34,059
ever. And in business there are hundreds of
examples where employees were ordered to stop

322
00:35:34,059 --> 00:35:41,650
work on projects that were later successful.
The Xbox was almost stopped by Microsoft,

323
00:35:41,650 --> 00:35:49,470
and the laser printer was nearly canceled
by Xerox because it was too expensive.

324
00:35:49,470 --> 00:35:57,099
When we see something unusual, we often refuse
it and look for reasons why it may fail. When

325
00:35:57,099 --> 00:36:03,730
managers see something new, they compare it
to things that were successful in the past.

326
00:36:03,730 --> 00:36:10,640
So some publishers thought Harry Potter was
too long for a children's book. And television

327
00:36:10,640 --> 00:36:16,130
company managers thought Seinfeld was too
much about New York to be of interest to the

328
00:36:16,130 --> 00:36:19,349
rest of the country.

329
00:36:19,349 --> 00:36:25,640
Test audiences are no better than managers
at judging new television shows. They make

330
00:36:25,640 --> 00:36:32,460
the same mistakes. When you watch a show at
home, in your living room, you get interested

331
00:36:32,460 --> 00:36:39,799
in the story. If you laugh a lot, at the end
you will think it was funny. But in a test

332
00:36:39,799 --> 00:36:46,410
audience you don't watch in the same way.
You know you are there to judge it, and so

333
00:36:46,410 --> 00:36:53,670
you compare it with shows you know are funny.
Neither test audiences nor managers are a

334
00:36:53,670 --> 00:37:00,390
good way of deciding whether a show is funny
or not.

335
00:37:00,390 --> 00:37:05,489
Wide experience and deep experience

336
00:37:05,489 --> 00:37:11,549
When the test audiences were negative about
Seinfeld, the project nearly stopped. But

337
00:37:11,549 --> 00:37:20,369
one man, Rick Ludwin, believed in it. Rick
Ludwin worked on special programs, not comedy,

338
00:37:20,369 --> 00:37:27,970
so Seinfeld wasn't his department. But, because
his experience was in a different type of

339
00:37:27,970 --> 00:37:35,400
television, he felt differently about the
project. Most comedy programs before Seinfeld

340
00:37:35,400 --> 00:37:42,869
had a few complete stories, with endings,
inside 22 minutes of television. Seinfeld

341
00:37:42,869 --> 00:37:50,290
started a lot more stories but sometimes didn't
finish them. That worried most television

342
00:37:50,290 --> 00:37:58,210
managers, but Ludwin worked on specials, where
each program is organized in its own way.

343
00:37:58,210 --> 00:38:05,799
Ludwin had written jokes for Bob Hope in the
1970s and had worked on comedies in the past.

344
00:38:05,799 --> 00:38:11,881
Because Ludwin had some experience of comedy,
he understood how it worked. And, although

345
00:38:11,881 --> 00:38:18,220
he hadn't worked in comedy for many years,
he had a wide experience of television, and

346
00:38:18,220 --> 00:38:25,140
he was happy to explore new ways of making
people laugh. He combined a wide experience

347
00:38:25,140 --> 00:38:31,539
of television outside of comedy with a deep
experience of comedy from his days writing

348
00:38:31,539 --> 00:38:40,460
jokes. And combining wide and deep experience
is very important for creativity.

349
00:38:40,460 --> 00:38:50,200
A recent study looked at every Nobel Prize-winning
scientist from 1901 to 2005 and compared them

350
00:38:50,200 --> 00:38:57,380
with other scientists who had not won Nobel
Prizes. Both groups knew their science well

351
00:38:57,380 --> 00:39:04,509
- they had deep experience. But the Nobel
Prize winners were more likely to be doing

352
00:39:04,509 --> 00:39:11,609
other, artistic, things as well. Here's what
the fifteen researchers at Michigan State

353
00:39:11,609 --> 00:39:24,349
University found when they compared the Nobel
Prize winners with the 

354
00:39:24,349 --> 00:39:59,460
other scientists.

355
00:39:59,460 --> 00:40:06,651
A study of thousands of Americans showed similar
results for entrepreneurs and inventors. These

356
00:40:06,651 --> 00:40:13,579
people were more likely than others to take
part in activities like drawing, painting,

357
00:40:13,579 --> 00:40:15,720
or writing.

358
00:40:15,720 --> 00:40:21,970
In a study of the fashion industry, a team
of researchers led by Frederic Godart looked

359
00:40:21,970 --> 00:40:29,289
at the cultural experience of fashion designers.
The most creative work came from designers

360
00:40:29,289 --> 00:40:35,809
who had worked in foreign countries, but Godart
found three especially interesting things

361
00:40:35,809 --> 00:40:38,410
about this experience.

362
00:40:38,410 --> 00:40:45,479
Firstly, living in a foreign country didn't
help creativity. It was working there that

363
00:40:45,479 --> 00:40:51,990
was important. The most original work came
from designers who had worked in two or three

364
00:40:51,990 --> 00:41:01,160
different countries. Secondly, the more foreign
the country the better. For an American, working

365
00:41:01,160 --> 00:41:10,800
in Canada didn't help a lot. Working in Korea
or Japan helped more with originality. Thirdly,

366
00:41:10,800 --> 00:41:18,089
the experience was better if it was deep.
A few weeks wasn't useful; the most creative

367
00:41:18,089 --> 00:41:24,430
designers had spent thirty-five years working
in other countries.

368
00:41:24,430 --> 00:41:30,019
Where Steve Jobs went wrong

369
00:41:30,019 --> 00:41:36,930
When Steve Jobs first got on a Segway, he
refused to climb off. When Dean Kamen wanted

370
00:41:36,930 --> 00:41:44,280
other investors to try it, Jobs let them,
but soon got back on again. He invited Kamen

371
00:41:44,280 --> 00:41:53,390
to dinner and told him his Segway was as original
as the computer, and he wanted to be involved.

372
00:41:53,390 --> 00:41:59,049
Steve Jobs was famous for making decisions
through intuition, rather than investigating

373
00:41:59,049 --> 00:42:07,390
carefully. Why did he get it wrong this time?
There were three main reasons: he didn't have

374
00:42:07,390 --> 00:42:13,440
experience of this area of business; he felt
too confident because of his success in other

375
00:42:13,440 --> 00:42:18,829
areas of business; and he was very enthusiastic.

376
00:42:18,829 --> 00:42:26,650
Let's start with experience. Jobs and the
other early investors in Segway, like Jeff

377
00:42:26,650 --> 00:42:34,029
Bezos, knew nothing about transportation.
They were originals in their area, but that

378
00:42:34,029 --> 00:42:41,809
did not make them good in other areas. Intuition
can be helpful, but it works best when we

379
00:42:41,809 --> 00:42:47,769
have experience of what we are looking at.
The Segway was a brilliant machine, and it

380
00:42:47,769 --> 00:42:54,380
was huge fun to ride it. But it was difficult
for people with no transportation experience

381
00:42:54,380 --> 00:42:57,489
to judge it.

382
00:42:57,489 --> 00:43:04,050
One man who did understand the problems with
Segway was Randy Komisar. He looked at the

383
00:43:04,050 --> 00:43:10,390
transportation market and realized that the
Segway wasn't going to replace the car: it

384
00:43:10,390 --> 00:43:17,720
would replace walking or cycling. But he didn't
think it was a product many people would want.

385
00:43:17,720 --> 00:43:23,390
It was exciting to ride, but it was a lot
of money to pay for something that replaced

386
00:43:23,390 --> 00:43:30,920
walking. And, at that time, nobody knew whether
governments would allow it on sidewalks. Komisar

387
00:43:30,920 --> 00:43:38,390
thought there would be a market in mail or
police services, or for golfers. But Jobs

388
00:43:38,390 --> 00:43:43,140
still thought that Segway was too exciting
to fail.

389
00:43:43,140 --> 00:43:50,390
Jobs' next problem was that he had been very
successful in one area of business, so he

390
00:43:50,390 --> 00:43:57,479
thought he understood all areas of business.
The more successful people are in the past,

391
00:43:57,479 --> 00:44:03,720
the worse they perform when they work in a
new area. He was so sure his intuition was

392
00:44:03,720 --> 00:44:11,970
right that he didn't check his intuition with
people who understood transportation.

393
00:44:11,970 --> 00:44:17,890
When Kamen talked with investors like Jobs
about Segway, he spoke about countries like

394
00:44:17,890 --> 00:44:25,450
China and India, which were building cities
the size of New York every year. These cities

395
00:44:25,450 --> 00:44:33,479
would be full of cars, and that would be really
bad for the environment. He was enthusiastic,

396
00:44:33,479 --> 00:44:41,240
and the investors liked that enthusiasm. When
we look at a new idea, the enthusiasm of the

397
00:44:41,240 --> 00:44:48,289
inventor can make a big difference. Enthusiasm
is important for inventors, but entrepreneurs

398
00:44:48,289 --> 00:44:53,079
need to be more careful.

399
00:44:53,079 --> 00:44:56,880
Thoughts on selecting ideas

400
00:44:56,880 --> 00:45:04,640
My failure to invest in Warby Parker was a
big false negative. I had never owned glasses,

401
00:45:04,640 --> 00:45:11,150
so it was hard for me to think about people
who did. I had deep experience of glasses:

402
00:45:11,150 --> 00:45:17,269
I had spent two years doing research in a
company that made and sold glasses through

403
00:45:17,269 --> 00:45:24,839
stores. But I didn't have wide experience.
Three of the four men behind Warby Parker

404
00:45:24,839 --> 00:45:32,900
wore glasses, and the fourth, Neil Blumenthal,
had worked for five years in Asia, Africa,

405
00:45:32,900 --> 00:45:38,920
and Latin America, helping women to start
businesses. One of the businesses he helped

406
00:45:38,920 --> 00:45:45,039
with was selling glasses, so he knew that
glasses could be made much more cheaply than

407
00:45:45,039 --> 00:45:48,210
people think.

408
00:45:48,210 --> 00:45:54,920
The Warby Parker entrepreneurs were also careful
to get everybody in the company involved in

409
00:45:54,920 --> 00:46:01,750
development. Nothing was secret, and ideas
were shared on a Google document, where everybody

410
00:46:01,750 --> 00:46:09,749
in the company could read them. And people
could give feedback on new ideas as they appeared.

411
00:46:09,749 --> 00:46:17,020
If Segway had done the same as Warby Parker,
they may have avoided some of their problems.

412
00:46:17,020 --> 00:46:25,390
But Kamen is still a great inventor, especially
in the area of healthcare. As an inventor,

413
00:46:25,390 --> 00:46:31,440
he should be having the great ideas but then
sharing them with others and getting feedback

414
00:46:31,440 --> 00:46:36,670
on which inventions are the most useful.

415
00:46:36,670 --> 00:46:45,529
In 2013, 300,000 patents were taken out in
the United States. The chances that any of

416
00:46:45,529 --> 00:46:53,170
these inventions will change the world are
tiny. One creative inventor, with lots of

417
00:46:53,170 --> 00:47:01,119
inventions, has a better chance that one invention
over his or her whole life will make a difference.

418
00:47:01,119 --> 00:47:06,930
And when we judge these inventors, we don't
look at their least successful ones: we look

419
00:47:06,930 --> 00:47:11,190
at the best.

420
00:47:11,190 --> 00:47:14,130
CHAPTER THREE
Speaking the truth

421
00:47:14,130 --> 00:47:25,210
In the early 1990s, a CIA (Central Intelligence
Agency) employee called Carmen Medina worked

422
00:47:25,210 --> 00:47:32,190
in Europe for three years. When she returned
to the United States, she found that leaving

423
00:47:32,190 --> 00:47:37,630
the United States had made it difficult to
get an interesting job in the CIA, and she

424
00:47:37,630 --> 00:47:42,229
began to look for other ways to help the organization.

425
00:47:42,229 --> 00:47:48,369
During the time she worked for the CIA in
Europe, she had noticed that there was a big

426
00:47:48,369 --> 00:47:56,730
problem with information sharing in the organization.
Information was shared by "finished intelligence

427
00:47:56,730 --> 00:48:03,960
reports," which were sent out once a day.
The experts who wrote them had no way of sharing

428
00:48:03,960 --> 00:48:11,450
ideas before the reports went out. Things
change very quickly in intelligence, and it

429
00:48:11,450 --> 00:48:19,069
was taking too long for the right information
to reach the right people. Carmen Medina suggested

430
00:48:19,069 --> 00:48:25,680
that, instead of using printed-paper documents,
departments could put their ideas immediately

431
00:48:25,680 --> 00:48:31,109
on to Intelink, a secret internet used by
the CIA.

432
00:48:31,109 --> 00:48:38,109
Her managers weren't interested. The internet
was dangerous, and intelligence had to be

433
00:48:38,109 --> 00:48:45,900
secret. With printed documents, you could
be sure the right people had the right information.

434
00:48:45,900 --> 00:48:52,489
It would be very dangerous if the wrong people
got secret information.

435
00:48:52,489 --> 00:49:00,789
Medina kept talking about her idea, but everybody
told her to be quiet. Finally, she decided

436
00:49:00,789 --> 00:49:08,549
to leave the CIA, but she couldn't find another
job. She ended up working in a boring CIA

437
00:49:08,549 --> 00:49:16,719
desk job, and she kept quiet about her idea
for a while. Three years later, she decided

438
00:49:16,719 --> 00:49:22,410
to argue again for online information sharing.

439
00:49:22,410 --> 00:49:29,880
Less than ten years later, Carmen Medina was
involved in creating Intellipedia, a Wikipedia

440
00:49:29,880 --> 00:49:38,219
for intelligence organizations. It allowed
departments to read reports from other organizations.

441
00:49:38,219 --> 00:49:44,029
It was a big change to the secret culture
of the CIA, and it helped with intelligence

442
00:49:44,029 --> 00:49:52,700
for the Beijing Olympics and after the Mumbai
attacks in 2008. In a few years, Intellipedia

443
00:49:52,700 --> 00:50:01,440
had half a million users and over 1 million
pages. It achieved this very quickly and very

444
00:50:01,440 --> 00:50:04,789
cheaply, too.

445
00:50:04,789 --> 00:50:10,280
Why did Medina fail the first time she talked
about information sharing, and why was she

446
00:50:10,280 --> 00:50:19,640
heard the second time? In between, the world
had changed. The internet was much more widely

447
00:50:19,640 --> 00:50:26,849
used, and the attacks of September 11, 2001
made it clear that intelligence organizations

448
00:50:26,849 --> 00:50:33,779
needed to be better at sharing information.
Medina had also become deputy director of

449
00:50:33,779 --> 00:50:41,249
intelligence at the CIA, which gave her the
power to follow her idea. She got that position

450
00:50:41,249 --> 00:50:48,440
by learning to speak in ways that made people
listen to her and believe her.

451
00:50:48,440 --> 00:50:54,329
We have all sometimes wanted to speak about
something that seems wrong either inside or

452
00:50:54,329 --> 00:51:03,230
outside of an organization. This chapter is
about how to do this well, and without risks.

453
00:51:03,230 --> 00:51:10,290
What are the right times to speak, and how
can we make sure people hear us? As well as

454
00:51:10,290 --> 00:51:16,410
Carmen Medina, we'll hear about an entrepreneur
who tells investors why they shouldn't invest

455
00:51:16,410 --> 00:51:23,750
in his companies; a manager who argued with
Steve Jobs; and why managers who appear to

456
00:51:23,750 --> 00:51:32,260
support you sometimes provide the least support.
We'll also see how gender and race affect

457
00:51:32,260 --> 00:51:39,190
our ability to be heard, and why the photos
we like of ourselves are the opposite of the

458
00:51:39,190 --> 00:51:42,660
ones we like of our friends.

459
00:51:42,660 --> 00:51:48,219
Power without status

460
00:51:48,219 --> 00:51:56,309
Leaders and managers like it when employees
offer help, do research, or ask for feedback.

461
00:51:56,309 --> 00:52:04,059
But there's one thing that is not so popular:
making suggestions. In one piece of research

462
00:52:04,059 --> 00:52:10,339
in an industry, it was found that the more
employees made suggestions to their managers

463
00:52:10,339 --> 00:52:15,259
the less likely they were to get promoted.

464
00:52:15,259 --> 00:52:21,969
To understand what happens in organizations
when people like Carmen Medina object to something,

465
00:52:21,969 --> 00:52:29,539
we need to think about power and status. Power
is being able to control what other people

466
00:52:29,539 --> 00:52:38,490
do; status is being admired by other people.
When people without status make suggestions,

467
00:52:38,490 --> 00:52:43,650
we don't think they should tell us what to
do, and we refuse. That is what happened to

468
00:52:43,650 --> 00:52:51,599
Carmen Medina; her years working outside of
the United States meant she had low status.

469
00:52:51,599 --> 00:52:57,329
She hadn't been able to show people what she
could really do, so people didn't value her

470
00:52:57,329 --> 00:52:59,549
ideas.

471
00:52:59,549 --> 00:53:05,460
Years later, she had earned status because
she had slowly gotten jobs with more responsibility

472
00:53:05,460 --> 00:53:12,509
in the organization. Then she got a job where
she had to protect sensitive information.

473
00:53:12,509 --> 00:53:20,029
Now, when she talked about sharing information,
it was part of her job. People saw that she

474
00:53:20,029 --> 00:53:27,499
stood for something and not against it. They
started to admire her work, and this made

475
00:53:27,499 --> 00:53:35,769
it possible for her ideas to be seen as original.
We don't like originality in low-status people,

476
00:53:35,769 --> 00:53:42,200
but we admire it when their status is high.

477
00:53:42,200 --> 00:53:45,819
The Sarick Effect

478
00:53:45,819 --> 00:53:52,739
After having their first child, Rufus Griscom
and Alisa Volkman were shocked by the false

479
00:53:52,739 --> 00:53:59,690
advertising and bad advice being offered to
parents. They started an online magazine called

480
00:53:59,690 --> 00:54:08,130
Babble that aimed to tell the truth about
being a parent. In 2009, when Griscom tried

481
00:54:08,130 --> 00:54:14,349
to get investors for the project, he did the
opposite to what every entrepreneur is taught

482
00:54:14,349 --> 00:54:22,880
to do. He told the investors the top five
reasons for not investing in his business.

483
00:54:22,880 --> 00:54:29,210
That should have killed the idea. Investors
are looking for reasons to say yes, and he

484
00:54:29,210 --> 00:54:35,519
was giving them reasons to say no. Entrepreneurs
are supposed to talk about the great things

485
00:54:35,519 --> 00:54:45,950
in the company, and he was doing the opposite.
But it worked. That year, Babble got 3.3 million

486
00:54:45,950 --> 00:54:49,109
dollars from investors.

487
00:54:49,109 --> 00:54:55,769
Two years later, Griscom went to see Disney
to see if they were interested in buying Babble.

488
00:54:55,769 --> 00:55:02,849
He did the same thing again and told them:
"Here's why you should not buy Babble.'' Then

489
00:55:02,849 --> 00:55:09,089
he explained that people who looked at the
Babble website didn't stay very long. And

490
00:55:09,089 --> 00:55:14,890
Babble was supposed to be for parents, but
40 percent of the messages people wrote on

491
00:55:14,890 --> 00:55:22,190
it weren't about parents at all. What's more,
the technology behind the website needed some

492
00:55:22,190 --> 00:55:30,339
serious work. Disney bought the company, for
40 million dollars.

493
00:55:30,339 --> 00:55:37,459
This is called the Sarick Effect, after Leslie
Sarick. Griscom was talking to people who

494
00:55:37,459 --> 00:55:44,509
had more power than him. He was asking them
to give him money. Usually you would tell

495
00:55:44,509 --> 00:55:50,269
people what was good about your project, but
that only works when people are already on

496
00:55:50,269 --> 00:55:56,980
your side. When you're talking to investors,
they are looking for reasons why your idea

497
00:55:56,980 --> 00:56:05,890
won't work. In that situation, it may be better
to talk about what is wrong with your idea.

498
00:56:05,890 --> 00:56:11,019
Here are four reasons why the Sarick Effect
can work.

499
00:56:11,019 --> 00:56:17,239
First, beginning with what is weak about a
business helps to put the audience on your

500
00:56:17,239 --> 00:56:25,459
side. When we know somebody is trying to push
us into buying something we usually refuse.

501
00:56:25,459 --> 00:56:31,170
But when Griscom said the words "Here's why
you shouldn't buy this company," they laughed

502
00:56:31,170 --> 00:56:36,729
and then relaxed. He had given them a problem
to solve.

503
00:56:36,729 --> 00:56:44,319
Second, talking about what is wrong with an
idea makes you look intelligent. People who

504
00:56:44,319 --> 00:56:50,529
say and write negative things are usually
seen to be more intelligent than people who

505
00:56:50,529 --> 00:56:57,559
say and write positive things. When you say
something negative about an idea, it shows

506
00:56:57,559 --> 00:57:04,369
you have thought about it. In Griscom's case,
it showed he knew there were problems, and

507
00:57:04,369 --> 00:57:07,460
he wasn't trying to hide them.

508
00:57:07,460 --> 00:57:13,530
Third, talking about the problems with your
business means that investors will trust you

509
00:57:13,530 --> 00:57:21,259
more. When Griscom talked about his problems,
it made him look honest. Of course, talking

510
00:57:21,259 --> 00:57:27,249
about the problems doesn't work if your audience
doesn't know about them, but Griscom's audiences

511
00:57:27,249 --> 00:57:33,009
were going to give him a lot of money. They
were looking at his business very carefully,

512
00:57:33,009 --> 00:57:40,519
so he couldn't hide the problems anyway; they
would find them. Also, investors thought that,

513
00:57:40,519 --> 00:57:46,009
if he was admitting what was wrong with his
business, there was probably a lot that was

514
00:57:46,009 --> 00:57:48,039
right.

515
00:57:48,039 --> 00:57:56,289
Fourth, audiences are more likely to support
an idea when the problems are made clear.

516
00:57:56,289 --> 00:58:01,579
When Griscom told investors about the problems
with the business, it made it difficult for

517
00:58:01,579 --> 00:58:07,269
them to think of other problems with it, and
they began to think that maybe Griscom's problems

518
00:58:07,269 --> 00:58:11,799
weren't too bad.

519
00:58:11,799 --> 00:58:15,849
The unfamiliarity problem

520
00:58:15,849 --> 00:58:21,450
When you have spent weeks, months, or even
years thinking about your idea, you know it

521
00:58:21,450 --> 00:58:27,490
perfectly. It's not possible to imagine what
the idea sounds like to someone who is hearing

522
00:58:27,490 --> 00:58:36,539
it for the first time. So we often present
our ideas to people without enough information.

523
00:58:36,539 --> 00:58:42,829
If we want people to accept our original ideas,
we need to speak about them often, and then

524
00:58:42,829 --> 00:58:54,559
repeat what we said. To illustrate, which
of these two words do you like better?

525
00:58:54,559 --> 00:58:59,359
If you're like most people, you will choose
sarick.

526
00:58:59,359 --> 00:59:07,259
Robert Zajonc has described this. He showed
people nonsense words like iktitaf and sarick

527
00:59:07,259 --> 00:59:14,019
and asked them which they preferred. If they
had never seen either word before, they liked

528
00:59:14,019 --> 00:59:20,329
them equally. But when they had seen one of
the words twice before the test, they preferred

529
00:59:20,329 --> 00:59:28,279
that one. And if they had seen it five, ten,
or twenty-five times, they liked it even more.

530
00:59:28,279 --> 00:59:35,631
I used sarick four times earlier. There is
nothing called the Sarick Effect, and there

531
00:59:35,631 --> 00:59:42,009
is nobody called Leslie Sarick. I invented
them to show how seeing the word already can

532
00:59:42,009 --> 00:59:50,579
affect you. (Rufus Griscom is real, however,
and so is everyone else in this book.)

533
00:59:50,579 --> 00:59:57,729
My favorite test of this is when people looked
at photographs of themselves and their friends.

534
00:59:57,729 --> 01:00:04,599
Some of the photos were inverted - as though
in a mirror - and some were not. People liked

535
01:00:04,599 --> 01:00:09,739
the photos of their friends when they weren't
inverted - because that's how they are used

536
01:00:09,739 --> 01:00:15,950
to seeing them. But they preferred photos
of themselves that were inverted - because

537
01:00:15,950 --> 01:00:20,859
we're used to seeing ourselves in the mirror.

538
01:00:20,859 --> 01:00:28,240
One reason for this is that the idea or picture
we're used to is easier to understand. Something

539
01:00:28,240 --> 01:00:36,259
that we don't know takes more effort, and
that makes us uncomfortable.

540
01:00:36,259 --> 01:00:39,989
Making people uncomfortable

541
01:00:39,989 --> 01:00:45,990
When Carmen Medina made no progress the first
time she talked about information sharing,

542
01:00:45,990 --> 01:00:52,789
she thought about leaving the CIA. She stayed,
but she didn't speak up to her managers again

543
01:00:52,789 --> 01:01:00,150
about her ideas for a long time. When she
did, it was because of her manager, Mike.

544
01:01:00,150 --> 01:01:08,609
I guessed Mike would be a friendly, relaxed
man, but he was the opposite. He was not friendly,

545
01:01:08,609 --> 01:01:16,089
and he got angry quickly. So why was he the
right manager for Medina?

546
01:01:16,089 --> 01:01:23,279
Although he was a difficult man, Mike did
care about the future of the organization.

547
01:01:23,279 --> 01:01:28,410
Friendly people like everyone around them
to be happy, so they are less likely to push

548
01:01:28,410 --> 01:01:36,260
difficult ideas forward. A man like Mike didn't
mind making people uncomfortable, so he was

549
01:01:36,260 --> 01:01:43,470
ready to give Medina time to develop her uncomfortable
ideas.

550
01:01:43,470 --> 01:01:48,509
Another thing that Medina noticed was that
middle managers were the most unhappy with

551
01:01:48,509 --> 01:01:55,789
her ideas. It is often the people in the middle
who don't want to make difficulties. They

552
01:01:55,789 --> 01:02:01,769
have made some progress in the organization
and don't want to go backward.

553
01:02:01,769 --> 01:02:07,849
The difficulties of speaking up

554
01:02:07,849 --> 01:02:13,869
Speaking up to, an audience of middle managers
is always a risk, but it was especially difficult

555
01:02:13,869 --> 01:02:20,229
for Carmen Medina because she was a woman
in an organization where most of the employees

556
01:02:20,229 --> 01:02:27,600
were men. I thought the days when women could
not speak up in work were in the past. But

557
01:02:27,600 --> 01:02:35,599
I soon realized there is still a problem with
gender. In organizations around the world,

558
01:02:35,599 --> 01:02:42,719
people expect men to speak up, and to lead.
But when women speak up they can be seen as

559
01:02:42,719 --> 01:02:45,479
angry.

560
01:02:45,479 --> 01:02:52,029
When I looked at my own research, I was very
disappointed. In an international bank and

561
01:02:52,029 --> 01:02:59,119
a healthcare company, I found that suggesting
good ideas led to promotions for men, but

562
01:02:59,119 --> 01:03:07,069
not for women. Other research shows that male
employees who talk more than others are rewarded

563
01:03:07,069 --> 01:03:16,059
and promoted. But women who talk more are
judged negatively by both men and women. When

564
01:03:16,059 --> 01:03:21,989
women suggest changing something at work to
improve it, their bosses don't trust them

565
01:03:21,989 --> 01:03:26,420
and are not as likely to change anything.

566
01:03:26,420 --> 01:03:32,259
There is no doubt things were difficult for
Medina because she was a woman in an organization

567
01:03:32,259 --> 01:03:41,369
of mostly men. But she was also a Puerto Rican.
Being from two groups like this makes a difference.

568
01:03:41,369 --> 01:03:48,299
Ashleigh Rosette, an African-American researcher,
found that people behaved differently when

569
01:03:48,299 --> 01:03:56,940
she spoke up than when white women and black
men did. When black women leaders failed,

570
01:03:56,940 --> 01:04:03,640
they were judged harder than black men, or
than white men and women.

571
01:04:03,640 --> 01:04:08,809
The road not taken

572
01:04:08,809 --> 01:04:17,289
In 1985, Donna Dubinsky was working as Apple's
distribution and sales manager. It was a busy

573
01:04:17,289 --> 01:04:25,460
job, as sales of Apple computers were increasing
quickly. Then Steve Jobs suggested that Apple

574
01:04:25,460 --> 01:04:33,420
stop using its six distribution centers and
move to "just-in-time" distribution: computers

575
01:04:33,420 --> 01:04:38,140
would be finished in the factory when they
were needed and would be delivered to customers

576
01:04:38,140 --> 01:04:41,759
direct from the factory.

577
01:04:41,759 --> 01:04:49,069
Dubinsky thought this was a big mistake. She
knew that Apple's success depended on successful

578
01:04:49,069 --> 01:04:56,989
distribution. She objected, but nobody listened.
For several months, she worked in a group

579
01:04:56,989 --> 01:05:02,810
that looked at just-in-time distribution.
Everyone seemed happy to go ahead with the

580
01:05:02,810 --> 01:05:11,209
new just-in-time system, except Dubinsky.
She spoke up against the idea and told Apple

581
01:05:11,209 --> 01:05:16,790
they must give her thirty days to create a
different system - and if they didn't give

582
01:05:16,790 --> 01:05:20,999
it to her she would leave.

583
01:05:20,999 --> 01:05:28,660
She was taking a big risk, but she was given
the time. At the end of the thirty days, she

584
01:05:28,660 --> 01:05:35,749
suggested a new distribution system, and it
was accepted. People knew she had done a good

585
01:05:35,749 --> 01:05:43,089
job in the past - she had status. Many people
would think that arguing with Steve Jobs,

586
01:05:43,089 --> 01:05:50,079
known as a difficult man, would not be a good
idea. But Jobs liked people who argued with

587
01:05:50,079 --> 01:05:57,719
him, and he was open to new ways of doing
things. And Dubinsky wasn't doing it for herself,

588
01:05:57,719 --> 01:06:03,489
she was doing it for Apple. Jobs understood
that.

589
01:06:03,489 --> 01:06:12,410
In 1991, Dubinsky left Apple. She met Jeff
Hawkins and joined Palm Computing, which produced

590
01:06:12,410 --> 01:06:20,980
the PalmPilot, one of the first small handheld
computers. But when Palm was bought by 3Com

591
01:06:20,980 --> 01:06:27,829
she was again unhappy with the management.
She and Hawkins left to start a new company,

592
01:06:27,829 --> 01:06:35,329
Handspring, which made handheld computers
and developed a smartphone. A few years later,

593
01:06:35,329 --> 01:06:39,589
Apple developed the iPhone.

594
01:06:39,589 --> 01:06:47,369
Medina had wanted to leave the CIA but couldn't.
That was why she stayed and, in the end, changed

595
01:06:47,369 --> 01:06:55,259
the organization from the inside. Dubinsky
did leave and helped to begin the smartphone

596
01:06:55,259 --> 01:07:03,339
revolution. Although Medina stayed and Dubinsky
left, they both chose to speak up rather than

597
01:07:03,339 --> 01:07:07,859
remain silent.

598
01:07:07,859 --> 01:07:10,130
CHAPTER FOUR
Taking time

599
01:07:10,130 --> 01:07:19,769
Late at night in a hotel room, a young man
stared at an empty piece of paper on the desk.

600
01:07:19,769 --> 01:07:27,210
Nervously, he called a friend in a room several
floors down to talk through some ideas. The

601
01:07:27,210 --> 01:07:34,910
friend ran up the stairs to discuss a speech
that would change history. At 3 a.m. the young

602
01:07:34,910 --> 01:07:44,910
man was still working. It was August 1963,
and, although he expected to speak to 100,000

603
01:07:44,910 --> 01:07:51,170
people in Washington the next day, Martin
Luther King, Jr. still hadn't finished his

604
01:07:51,170 --> 01:07:52,319
speech.

605
01:07:52,319 --> 01:08:00,280
"He worked on it all night, not sleeping,"
King's wife, Coretta, remembered. "He was

606
01:08:00,280 --> 01:08:06,339
