623
01:09:56,290 --> 01:09:57,310
Great procrastinators

624
01:09:57,310 --> 01:10:07,601
Recently, a student of mine, Jihae Shin, came
to me with an interesting idea: procrastinating

625
01:10:07,601 --> 01:10:15,291
might be good for originality. When you procrastinate
you may be thinking about the thing you have

626
01:10:15,291 --> 01:10:22,560
to do, but you delay doing it. Shin wondered
whether the delay meant that you had time

627
01:10:22,560 --> 01:10:30,420
to think about a number of different possibilities,
rather than just one idea. As a result, you

628
01:10:30,420 --> 01:10:37,790
may have more original ideas. I asked her
to test her theory.

629
01:10:37,790 --> 01:10:44,620
There was an empty building at college, where
there had been a small food store. Shin asked

630
01:10:44,620 --> 01:10:52,290
students to write ideas for using the empty
space. When the students started work immediately,

631
01:10:52,290 --> 01:10:57,830
most of their ideas weren't very original
- they suggested things like another food

632
01:10:57,830 --> 01:11:06,940
store. But Shin asked some students to procrastinate
by giving them computer games to play first.

633
01:11:06,940 --> 01:11:13,670
The business ideas these students produced
were more original. The ideas from the procrastinators

634
01:11:13,670 --> 01:11:18,150
were 28 percent more original.

635
01:11:18,150 --> 01:11:25,460
We were excited by these results but wondered
