636
01:11:25,460 --> 01:11:32,180
But when people played games before they were
asked for ideas, it didn't help originality.

637
01:11:32,180 --> 01:11:39,910
It also didn't help to start work, then stop
and take a break, and then return to work.

638
01:11:39,910 --> 01:11:46,460
Once the students had started work, they had
made too much progress to stop and start again.

639
01:11:46,460 --> 01:11:54,470
They had to know what was wanted, and to procrastinate,
in order to have the most creative ideas.

640
01:11:54,470 --> 01:12:02,620
Shin then did some more research, looking
at a Korean furniture company. Managers thought

641
01:12:02,620 --> 01:12:10,080
employees who procrastinated a lot were more
original than those who didn't. But procrastinating

642
01:12:10,080 --> 01:12:17,980
wasn't always a good thing: if the employees
weren't really determined to solve a big problem,

643
01:12:17,980 --> 01:12:25,310
delaying just made things late. But, when
they were excited about looking for new ideas,

644
01:12:25,310 --> 01:12:27,450
procrastination helped a lot.

645
01:12:27,450 --> 01:12:35,970
Leonardo da Vinci was a famous procrastinator.
Experts think he took sixteen years to paint

646
01:12:35,970 --> 01:12:43,230
the Mona Lisa, stopping and starting many
times. He also spent fifteen years thinking

647
01:12:43,230 --> 01:12:50,120
about The Last Supper, working on many other
things at the same time.

648
01:12:50,120 --> 01:12:57,460
In American history, there may be only one
speech as famous as King's: Abraham Lincoln's

649
01:12:57,460 --> 01:13:06,820
Gettysburg Address. In just 272 words, Lincoln
made clear that the Civil War was about freedom

650
01:13:06,820 --> 01:13:14,810
and equality. Lincoln was invited to give
the speech two weeks earlier. By the day before,

651
01:13:14,810 --> 01:13:20,570
