654
01:13:32,210 --> 01:13:38,040
In the summer before his "I have a dream"
speech, King got advice from three people

655
01:13:38,040 --> 01:13:44,560
about what he should say - and how. He also
discussed the speech for a long time with

656
01:13:44,560 --> 01:13:51,710
Clarence Jones, who had written some of his
other speeches. Jones and another man began

657
01:13:51,710 --> 01:13:59,120
to write some ideas for the speech. King waited
until the last four days before he began to

658
01:13:59,120 --> 01:14:06,000
work on the speech. Then, the night before,
he met with his advisors, and they started

659
01:14:06,000 --> 01:14:08,350
again.

660
01:14:08,350 --> 01:14:15,520
By delaying the work on the speech, King was
giving an example of the Zeigarnik effect.

661
01:14:15,520 --> 01:14:22,230
The Russian psychologist Bluma Zeigarnik showed
that people remember unfinished things better

662
01:14:22,230 --> 01:14:30,060
than finished things. Once something is finished,
we stop thinking about it. But if it's not

663
01:14:30,060 --> 01:14:36,970
finished, it is still there in our minds.
When King finally asked Jones to write the

664
01:14:36,970 --> 01:14:44,610
complete speech, he had a wide range of ideas.
But that wasn't the only good thing about

665
01:14:44,610 --> 01:14:46,500
procrastinating.

666
01:14:46,500 --> 01:14:51,510
"I have a dream"

667
01:14:51,510 --> 01:14:58,510
