679
01:16:17,730 --> 01:16:24,980
King had procrastinated, but he had given
more than 350 speeches in the year before

680
01:16:24,980 --> 01:16:31,790
the "I have a dream" speech. He had material
in his head that he could use when he needed

681
01:16:31,790 --> 01:16:41,110
it. He put his speeches together from pieces
of all his other speeches.

682
01:16:41,110 --> 01:16:44,710
Pioneers and settlers

683
01:16:44,710 --> 01:16:50,330
After working on starting over one hundred
new companies, Bill Gross did some research

684
01:16:50,330 --> 01:16:58,010
to find out why some companies succeeded and
others failed. The biggest reasons were not

685
01:16:58,010 --> 01:17:04,730
the quality of the ideas, the people in the
team, or the amount of money invested. "The

686
01:17:04,730 --> 01:17:13,110
number one thing was timing," Gross said.
42 percent of the difference between success

687
01:17:13,110 --> 01:17:17,370
and failure was timing.

688
01:17:17,370 --> 01:17:23,240
Most Americans believe it is better to be
the first mover. We want to be leaders, not

689
01:17:23,240 --> 01:17:29,090
followers. If you are the first to market
with a new product, you can learn about the

690
01:17:29,090 --> 01:17:37,011
market more quickly and get the most customers.
By doing that you stop the competition, because

691
01:17:37,011 --> 01:17:42,450
it will be hard to persuade those customers
to change.

692
01:17:42,450 --> 01:17:49,150
In a famous study, researchers Peter Colder
and Gerard Tellis compared the success of

693
01:17:49,150 --> 01:17:57,290
companies that were either pioneers or settlers.
Pioneers were the first movers: the first

694
01:17:57,290 --> 01:18:04,980
company to make or sell a product. The settlers
arrived later; they waited for the pioneers

695
01:18:04,980 --> 01:18:12,490
to create a market first. When Golder and
Tellis looked at hundreds of products in more

696
01:18:12,490 --> 01:18:20,550
than thirty different areas of business they
found a huge difference in failures: 47 percent

697
01:18:20,550 --> 01:18:28,770
for pioneers and just 8 percent for settlers.
And even when the pioneers did survive they

698
01:18:28,770 --> 01:18:36,540
only got around 10 percent of the market compared
with 28 percent for settlers.

699
01:18:36,540 --> 01:18:44,730
Surprisingly, the problems for the first mover
are often huge. Pioneers may sometimes get

700
01:18:44,730 --> 01:18:51,460
a big part of the market, but they usually
have a big risk of not surviving, and they

701
01:18:51,460 --> 01:18:58,980
often don't make much money. If you're thinking
of moving into a new area of business, you

702
01:18:58,980 --> 01:19:08,600
need to stop and think about timing. But researcher
Lisa Bolton found something more frightening.

703
01:19:08,600 --> 01:19:15,070
Even when entrepreneurs know it is risky to
be the first mover, they don't believe it.

704
01:19:15,070 --> 01:19:21,770
We can all think of pioneers who succeeded,
and we've forgotten those who failed. So what

705
01:19:21,770 --> 01:19:26,910
are the reasons that settlers do better than
pioneers?

706
01:19:26,910 --> 01:19:33,100
First, many people think that settlers are
just copying the pioneers, but that isn't

707
01:19:33,100 --> 01:19:40,690
really true. They may be waiting before introducing
something new. They may be working on something

708
01:19:40,690 --> 01:19:48,120
that is better than the products in the market
now. In home video games, the pioneer was

709
01:19:48,120 --> 01:19:57,910
Magnavox Odyssey, which started with simple
sports games in 1972. A settler, Nintendo,

710
01:19:57,910 --> 01:20:06,250
started to manage the distribution for Odyssey
in Japan in 1975 and then, in the 1980s, started

711
01:20:06,250 --> 01:20:14,380
to sell the Nintendo Entertainment System,
with games like Super Mario Bros. Nintendo's

712
01:20:14,380 --> 01:20:20,810
games improved on the older games; it was
easier to play them, and the characters were

713
01:20:20,810 --> 01:20:28,610
interesting. You don't have to be first to
be original. You have to be different and

714
01:20:28,610 --> 01:20:32,060
better.

715
01:20:32,060 --> 01:20:39,890
In the 1990s, a banker, Joseph Park, was at
home in his apartment. He was annoyed because

716
01:20:39,890 --> 01:20:46,200
he wanted to stay home and watch a movie,
but to do that he had to go out to a store

717
01:20:46,200 --> 01:20:53,460
and rent one. Why couldn't he go to a website,
choose a movie, and have it delivered to his

718
01:20:53,460 --> 01:20:59,700
door? As there didn't seem to be a company
that provided this service, Park decided to

719
01:20:59,700 --> 01:21:02,810
create one.

720
01:21:02,810 --> 01:21:10,670
Although Park collected 250 million dollars
from investors, his company, Kozmo, only survived

721
01:21:10,670 --> 01:21:19,620
until 2001. The biggest mistake was that Kozmo
promised to deliver movies in one hour, and

722
01:21:19,620 --> 01:21:25,940
spent a lot of money on distribution to try
and make that possible. If Park had moved

723
01:21:25,940 --> 01:21:34,030
more slowly, he might have realized that delivering
movies in an hour wasn't going to work. A

724
01:21:34,030 --> 01:21:41,250
lot of people wanted online movies, and Netflix
was just beginning. Maybe Kozmo could have

725
01:21:41,250 --> 01:21:49,060
competed with movies by mail, and then it
might have been able to move to delivery online.

726
01:21:49,060 --> 01:21:58,640
Second, it seems that people who choose to
move late may be better suited to succeed.

727
01:21:58,640 --> 01:22:05,190
Risk-takers like to move first, and they may
make their decisions too quickly. Entrepreneurs,

728
01:22:05,190 --> 01:22:12,350
who want to avoid risk, watch the market and
wait for the right time. In research into

729
01:22:12,350 --> 01:22:19,200
software companies, Elizabeth Pontikes and
William Barnett found that when entrepreneurs

730
01:22:19,200 --> 01:22:25,190
waited for the market to cool down, they were
more likely to succeed.

731
01:22:25,190 --> 01:22:32,190
Third, as well as avoiding some risk, settlers
can look at their competitors' products and

732
01:22:32,190 --> 01:22:41,020
make their own products better. When you are
first, you have to make all the mistakes yourself.

733
01:22:41,020 --> 01:22:45,700
Settlers can watch you and learn from your
mistakes.

734
01:22:45,700 --> 01:22:53,610
Fourth, pioneers often stay with the first
products they sell. Settlers can watch how

735
01:22:53,610 --> 01:23:01,170
the market changes and change their products
so they remain right for the changing market.

736
01:23:01,170 --> 01:23:08,150
Settlers can also wait for the market to be
ready for them. When Warby Parker started,

737
01:23:08,150 --> 01:23:13,310
people had been selling products online for
ten years, even though the idea hadn't worked

738
01:23:13,310 --> 01:23:16,770
before for glasses.

739
01:23:16,770 --> 01:23:24,040
The theory of pioneers and settlers is true
outside of the world of business as well.

740
01:23:24,040 --> 01:23:31,540
In the 1840s, the Hungarian doctor Ignaz Semmelweis
discovered that if medical students washed

741
01:23:31,540 --> 01:23:39,260
their hands the number of women patients who
died giving birth was much lower. Other doctors

742
01:23:39,260 --> 01:23:47,080
laughed at him. He became sick and died a
young man. Twenty years later, the research

743
01:23:47,080 --> 01:23:52,810
of Louis Pasteur and Robert Koch showed Semmelweis
to be right.

744
01:23:52,810 --> 01:23:59,140
I don't want to say that it is never good
to be first. If we all wait for someone else

745
01:23:59,140 --> 01:24:06,120
to move first, nothing original will ever
be created. Someone has to be the pioneer,

746
01:24:06,120 --> 01:24:12,350
and sometimes they are successful. This is
often true when there is a patent behind the

747
01:24:12,350 --> 01:24:19,870
product, or when a product becomes more valuable
as more people use it, such as social media.

748
01:24:19,870 --> 01:24:27,290
But in most cases the chances of success are
not higher if you move first. And when the

749
01:24:27,290 --> 01:24:35,740
market is not clear, or unknown, then being
a pioneer is a huge risk. The lesson here

750
01:24:35,740 --> 01:24:42,181
is that, if you have an original idea, it's
a mistake to think you must move first, before

751
01:24:42,181 --> 01:24:49,190
your competitors. Procrastinating can make
it easier to achieve something, and, in the

752
01:24:49,190 --> 01:24:58,560
same way, delaying market entry can give us
the chance to learn more and reduce risk.

753
01:24:58,560 --> 01:25:04,620
But what happens if we take a wider view than
ideas and products? If we look at the whole

754
01:25:04,620 --> 01:25:12,920
life of a person, is there a risk in waiting
too long?

755
01:25:12,920 --> 01:25:16,460
Conceptual and experimental

756
01:25:16,460 --> 01:25:23,620
It is widely believed that originality is
something we find in young people. Vinod Khosla

757
01:25:23,620 --> 01:25:29,460
said at the National Association of Software
and Services Companies Product Conclave in

758
01:25:29,460 --> 01:25:38,730
2011: "People under thirty-five are the people
who make change happen. People over forty-five

759
01:25:38,730 --> 01:25:46,390
die in terms of new ideas." Albert Einstein
also said that a scientist had to make his

760
01:25:46,390 --> 01:25:53,800
discoveries before the age of thirty. And
it is true that people do often lose their

761
01:25:53,800 --> 01:25:56,770
originality over time.

762
01:25:56,770 --> 01:26:04,050
But this doesn't always happen. When companies
have suggestion boxes, it seems that older

763
01:26:04,050 --> 01:26:10,350
employees have more and better ideas than
younger employees, with the highest-value

764
01:26:10,350 --> 01:26:18,510
ideas coming from employees over fifty-five.
And in new technology companies, the average

765
01:26:18,510 --> 01:26:23,870
age of entrepreneurs is thirty-eight.

766
01:26:23,870 --> 01:26:30,010
In art and science, David Galenson shows that
we're quick to remember the exciting young

767
01:26:30,010 --> 01:26:38,290
people, but there are a lot of older people
who succeed much later. In film, for example,

768
01:26:38,290 --> 01:26:45,210
