some people creative early, while others start

771
01:27:01,590 --> 01:27:05,510
to be creative later?

772
01:27:05,510 --> 01:27:13,640
The creative age depends on the way we think.
When Galenson studied creativity, he discovered

773
01:27:13,640 --> 01:27:22,570
two very different types of thinking: conceptual
and experimental. Conceptual people think

774
01:27:22,570 --> 01:27:30,491
of a big idea and try to achieve it. Experimental
people work by trying different things, some

775
01:27:30,491 --> 01:27:37,240
of which succeed, while some don't. They are
thinking about a problem, but they don't think

776
01:27:37,240 --> 01:27:44,010
about the answer to the problem when they
start work. They don't plan; they decide things

777
01:27:44,010 --> 01:27:47,220
as they work.

778
01:27:47,220 --> 01:27:53,650
Galenson believes conceptual thinkers move
quickly, while experimental thinkers take

779
01:27:53,650 --> 01:28:01,790
longer. He studied economists who had won
the Nobel Prize and discovered that on average

780
01:28:01,790 --> 01:28:08,060
the conceptual economists had done their best
work at forty-three, while the experimental

781
01:28:08,060 --> 01:28:16,250
economists had done theirs at sixty-one. A
study of physicists who had won the Nobel

782
01:28:16,250 --> 01:28:23,220
Prize discovered that half of those under
thirty were conceptual, while 92 percent of

783
01:28:23,220 --> 01:28:29,190
those over forty-five did experimental work.

784
01:28:29,190 --> 01:28:35,590
Conceptual people can work quickly because
they don't need to do years of careful research.

785
01:28:35,590 --> 01:28:41,150
They are also usually young, because young
people find it easier to approach a problem

786
01:28:41,150 --> 01:28:50,900
in a new way. But as they get older they find
it more difficult, and they become less original.

787
01:28:50,900 --> 01:28:58,000
This was Einstein's problem. His most important
discoveries were made in his head. They were

788
01:28:58,000 --> 01:29:04,130
ideas that explained things that had been
discovered by experimental scientists. As

789
01:29:04,130 --> 01:29:12,900
he got older, he found it more difficult to
work with some of the newer ideas in physics.

790
01:29:12,900 --> 01:29:18,820
Conceptual people have ideas earlier, but
then they risk copying themselves and producing

791
01:29:18,820 --> 01:29:27,060
very similar ideas. Being experimental takes
longer, but it means the scientist or artist

792
01:29:27,060 --> 01:29:34,920
is able to discover new ideas. Mark Twain
published Adventures of Huckleberry Finn when

793
01:29:34,920 --> 01:29:41,940
he was forty-nine, changing the story as he
wrote it. When he started, he didn't know

794
01:29:41,940 --> 01:29:45,460
how it was going to end.

795
01:29:45,460 --> 01:29:53,191
As we get older, it helps to be more experimental.
Leonardo da Vinci was experimental, taking

796
01:29:53,191 --> 01:30:00,360
years to finish his greatest paintings. Martin
Luther King, Jr., too, was experimental, giving

797
01:30:00,360 --> 01:30:07,900
thousands of speeches and changing them as
he did so. Moving quickly is fine for the

798
01:30:07,900 --> 01:30:15,940
