01:30:41,690 --> 01:30:48,940
She was the first woman in Massachusetts to
earn a college degree. She was the first American

804
01:30:48,940 --> 01:30:55,610
lecturer in women's rights. She was one of
only a very few women who spoke in public

805
01:30:55,610 --> 01:31:02,550
at all. She started the country's leading
women's newspaper, the Woman's Journal, which

806
01:31:02,550 --> 01:31:06,630
was published for fifty years.

807
01:31:06,630 --> 01:31:13,710
In 1851, Stone organized a women's rights
meeting, but she wasn't persuaded to speak

808
01:31:13,710 --> 01:31:20,880
until the last day. In her speech, she suggested
that women should ask the government for the

809
01:31:20,880 --> 01:31:28,220
right to vote and to own houses and land.
Her speech became known for pushing the women's

810
01:31:28,220 --> 01:31:35,510
rights movement forward. Her words were read
by John Stuart Mill and Harriet Taylor Mill

811
01:31:35,510 --> 01:31:42,410
in England, who later published a famous letter
about women's rights.

812
01:31:42,410 --> 01:31:50,050
After the speech, two other great women, Susan
B. Anthony and Elizabeth Cady Stanton, joined

813
01:31:50,050 --> 01:31:56,950
Stone, and together they worked for women's
suffrage. But a long time before they reached

814
01:31:56,950 --> 01:32:07,260
their goal the three women broke apart. In
1869, Anthony and Stanton left Stone's organization

815
01:32:07,260 --> 01:32:14,840
and started their own. Working separately,
the two organizations had little success,

816
01:32:14,840 --> 01:32:20,320
and the arguments between the three women
made many people think women weren't able

817
01:32:20,320 --> 01:32:27,050
to be leaders. When Stanton and Anthony wrote
a book about the history of the women's rights

818
01:32:27,050 --> 01:32:35,460
movement, Stone's name wasn't mentioned, if
all three leaders wanted the same thing, why

819
01:32:35,460 --> 01:32:39,530
did they fight so bitterly?

820
01:32:39,530 --> 01:32:45,530
This chapter looks at how originals build
coalitions to reach their goals and how to

821
01:32:45,530 --> 01:32:53,100
solve the problems that can lead to coalitions
failing. Coalitions can do a lot, but they

822
01:32:53,100 --> 01:33:00,400
can also break apart easily because they depend
on people's relationships. We will look at

823
01:33:00,400 --> 01:33:07,920
the difficulties of coalitions, at an entrepreneur's
battle to persuade people to try her idea,

824
01:33:07,920 --> 01:33:15,460
at a Disney movie that almost didn't get made,
and at how Occupy Wall Street failed. You

825
01:33:15,460 --> 01:33:23,320
will see how building good coalitions requires
a lot of work.

826
01:33:23,320 --> 01:33:29,550
The important lesson is the "Goldilocks" theory
of coalitions, which looks at the ideas within

827
01:33:29,550 --> 01:33:38,760
groups as too hot, too cold, or just right.
The originals who start a coalition are often

828
01:33:38,760 --> 01:33:47,590
the most enthusiastic people in it, and sometimes
their ideas are too hot for others. It's sometimes

829
01:33:47,590 --> 01:33:54,351
necessary to cool the message to encourage
other groups to join the coalition. The message

830
01:33:54,351 --> 01:34:05,110
needs to be neither too hot, nor too cold.
It needs to be just right.

831
01:34:05,110 --> 01:34:08,190
Groups that break

832
01:34:08,190 --> 01:34:14,410
We would expect that having similar goals
holds groups together, but very often, these

833
01:34:14,410 --> 01:34:21,720
goals drive groups apart. Even though people
share the same goals, some groups push their

834
01:34:21,720 --> 01:34:29,620
ideas further, and these groups are often
very critical of those who are less enthusiastic.

835
01:34:29,620 --> 01:34:37,030
In one study, vegetarians (who don't eat meat)
and vegans (who don't eat meat or any other

836
01:34:37,030 --> 01:34:45,150
animal products like milk or eggs) gave their
opinions about one another. Vegans disliked

837
01:34:45,150 --> 01:34:53,640
vegetarians three times as much as vegetarians
disliked vegans. The vegans with the strongest

838
01:34:53,640 --> 01:35:01,020
opinions thought that vegetarians were weak:
if they really cared about animals, they wouldn't

839
01:35:01,020 --> 01:35:08,650
eat animal products like eggs. The more strongly
you feel about something, the more you want

840
01:35:08,650 --> 01:35:13,400
to show you are different from people who
have some of your goals but who don't push

841
01:35:13,400 --> 01:35:17,470
their ideas as far as you do.

842
01:35:17,470 --> 01:35:24,260
This is why Anthony and Stanton broke away
from Lucy Stone. They wanted to push things

843
01:35:24,260 --> 01:35:32,170
further. Things got really bad when Anthony
and Stanton argued against giving African-American

844
01:35:32,170 --> 01:35:38,920
men the vote. If women couldn't vote, they
said, these men shouldn't be able to vote

845
01:35:38,920 --> 01:35:48,520
either. Stone did not agree; she wanted suffrage
for African Americans. Anthony and Stanton

846
01:35:48,520 --> 01:35:55,170
were very angry; they thought Stone was not
serious about women's suffrage, and they started

847
01:35:55,170 --> 01:36:02,820
their own women's suffrage organization. Stone
tried to calm things down, but for twenty

848
01:36:02,820 --> 01:36:09,520
years their two groups worked separately,
sometimes even against one another.

849
01:36:09,520 --> 01:36:17,220
Now there were two separate groups, they needed
to find new people to help them and form new

850
01:36:17,220 --> 01:36:26,070
coalitions. They all found help from an unexpected
group, the Women's Christian Temperance Union,

851
01:36:26,070 --> 01:36:33,410
a women's group that was trying to stop people
drinking alcohol. Men who drank alcohol were

852
01:36:33,410 --> 01:36:41,820
often violent with their wives, and their
families became poor. But the WCTU members

853
01:36:41,820 --> 01:36:48,261
were very different from the women's suffrage
groups. They were often women from rich, usually

854
01:36:48,261 --> 01:36:55,740
very religious, families who did not support
modern ideas. Yet the groups managed to work

855
01:36:55,740 --> 01:37:03,860
together. Many people across the country disliked
the idea of women's suffrage, and it's a surprise

856
01:37:03,860 --> 01:37:11,050
that the WCTU was happy to work with groups
who were pushing for it. But they did make

857
01:37:11,050 --> 01:37:18,900
progress, and, in several states, women achieved
the right to vote.

858
01:37:18,900 --> 01:37:24,840
The following example of a young, creative
entrepreneur shows how business coalitions

859
01:37:24,840 --> 01:37:30,220
can be built successfully.

860
01:37:30,220 --> 01:37:31,220
Building and breaking coalitions

861
01:37:31,220 --> 01:37:32,220
In 2011, a student called Meredith Perry realized
that there was a big problem with the world

862
01:37:32,220 --> 01:37:33,220
of technology. She didn't need a wire to make
a phone call or connect to the internet. Everything

863
01:37:33,220 --> 01:37:34,220
was wireless. Except for one thing. To use
her phone and her computer she still had to

864
01:37:34,220 --> 01:37:35,220
connect them to the wall to charge them. She
wanted wireless electricity.

865
01:37:35,220 --> 01:37:36,220
She thought about things that can send energy
through the air, like radio waves. But they

866
01:37:36,220 --> 01:37:37,220
wouldn't work well for electricity. What about
ultrasound? You can't see ultrasound, and

867
01:37:37,220 --> 01:37:38,220
it is silent. Could it be used to carry electrical
energy without wires?

868
01:37:38,220 --> 01:37:39,220
Her physics teachers said it was impossible;
so did ultrasound engineers. A lot of important

869
01:37:39,220 --> 01:37:40,220
people told her she was wasting her time.
Then she won an invention competition. But

870
01:37:40,220 --> 01:37:41,220
as an entrepreneur on her own, with no money,
she needed help.

871
01:37:41,220 --> 01:37:42,220
Three years later, I met Meredith Perry. She
had managed to get 750,000 dollars from investors,

872
01:37:42,220 --> 01:37:43,220
and she had the first example of a wireless
charger. It could charge things faster than

873
01:37:43,220 --> 01:37:44,220
a wire, and over longer distances, and it
would be in the stores in two years. By the

874
01:37:44,220 --> 01:37:45,220
end of 2014, her company, uBeam, had eighteen
patents, and investors had given it 10 million

875
01:37:45,220 --> 01:37:46,220
dollars. "Every single person that is now
working for the company didn't think it was

876
01:37:46,220 --> 01:37:47,220
possible," she said.

877
01:37:47,220 --> 01:37:48,220
Perry had had the same difficulty that all
originals have when they want to do something

878
01:37:48,220 --> 01:37:49,220
different. Most people don't want to change
things. She had talked to a lot of experts,

879
01:37:49,220 --> 01:37:50,220
and they all told her about the problems in
her math and her physics. In the end, she

880
01:37:50,220 --> 01:37:51,220
realized there was a problem with her message.
She had been saying: "I'm trying to build

881
01:37:51,220 --> 01:37:52,220
something that can send electricity through
the air." Instead, she said: "I'm looking

882
01:37:52,220 --> 01:37:53,220
for someone to make a part for this new product.
Can you help?"

883
01:37:53,220 --> 01:37:54,220
This worked. By breaking up the project into
parts, she found people who would design those

884
01:37:54,220 --> 01:37:55,220
parts. Soon she had people working on the
project. She stopped talking about the most

885
01:37:55,220 --> 01:37:56,220
exciting part of her idea, the wireless electricity,
because that shocked people. She had moved

886
01:37:56,220 --> 01:37:57,220
her question from why, to how. Instead of
talking about why she wanted something, she

887
01:37:57,220 --> 01:37:58,220
talked about how she needed to get there.
By talking about smaller parts of the project,

888
01:37:58,220 --> 01:37:59,220
she found people who would work with her.
When she couldn't find engineers to make a

889
01:37:59,220 --> 01:38:00,220
big jump, she found engineers who would take
a few small steps.

890
01:38:00,220 --> 01:38:01,220
Although it's usually a good idea for creative
people to explain why they want to do something,

891
01:38:01,220 --> 01:38:02,220
if their idea moves too far from what people
think is possible, it may just frighten them

892
01:38:02,220 --> 01:38:03,220
away.

893
01:38:03,220 --> 01:38:04,220
Coalitions often break up when one group is
more extreme than the other groups. Occupy

894
01:38:04,220 --> 01:38:05,220
Wall Street started in 2011, to argue against
the unequal sharing of money across the United

895
01:38:05,220 --> 01:38:06,220
States by the financial center of Wall Street
in New York. In 2011, most Americans supported

896
01:38:06,220 --> 01:38:07,220
the coalition, but support started to fall
as some groups in the coalition became too

897
01:38:07,220 --> 01:38:08,220
extreme. Srda Popovic has suggested that the
movement's mistake was to use the word "Occupy"

898
01:38:08,220 --> 01:38:09,220
in their name, which was about people camping
in the streets outside of banks and financial

899
01:38:09,220 --> 01:38:10,220
businesses. Although many people approved
of the general goals of the movement, they

900
01:38:10,220 --> 01:38:11,220
didn't like the idea of "occupying" a place,
because it was too extreme.

901
01:38:11,220 --> 01:38:12,220
In the women's suffrage movement, something
similar happened. Anthony and Stanton built

902
01:38:12,220 --> 01:38:13,220
a coalition with George Francis Train in 1867.
Train was popular, but he was strongly against

903
01:38:13,220 --> 01:38:14,220
giving African-American men the right to vote.
It was a dangerous coalition that didn't work.

904
01:38:14,220 --> 01:38:15,220
The state of Kansas was close to approving
women's suffrage but failed. And African-American

905
01:38:15,220 --> 01:38:16,220
men didn't get the right to vote in Kansas
either.

906
01:38:16,220 --> 01:38:17,220
Later, Anthony and Stanton put together a
coalition with Victoria Woodhull, who was

907
01:38:17,220 --> 01:38:18,220
a woman with very strong views and believed
that women should have the right to love who

908
01:38:18,220 --> 01:38:19,220
they wanted, and, as she said, "to change
that love every day if I please." This was

909
01:38:19,220 --> 01:38:20,220
too much for many people and frightened away
some of the supporters of women's suffrage.

910
01:38:20,220 --> 01:38:21,220
Many people think that this delayed women's
suffrage for twenty years.

911
01:38:21,220 --> 01:38:22,220
A recent study by Blake Ashforth and Peter
Reingen shows an interesting thing about coalitions.

912
01:38:22,220 --> 01:38:23,220
For people inside a coalition, the most important
people are the people at the center of the

913
01:38:23,220 --> 01:38:24,220
group. For the women's suffrage coalition,
this was Anthony and Stanton. But for people

914
01:38:24,220 --> 01:38:25,220
outside of a coalition, the person they notice
is the one with the most extreme ideas. In

915
01:38:25,220 --> 01:38:26,220
the women's suffrage coalition, that person
was Woodhull.

916
01:38:26,220 --> 01:38:27,220
Enemies are better than frenemies

917
01:38:27,220 --> 01:38:28,220
In The Godfather: Part II, Michael Corleone
says, "Keep your friends close, but your enemies

918
01:38:28,220 --> 01:38:29,220
closer." But what do we do with people who
are neither our friends, nor our enemies?

919
01:38:29,220 --> 01:38:30,220
Usually we see people as friends, enemies,
or as somewhere in between. Our closest friends

920
01:38:30,220 --> 01:38:31,220
support us all the time; our enemies are always
working against us. But in fact there are

921
01:38:31,220 --> 01:38:32,220
also people who we can call "frenemies." These
are people who sometimes support you and sometimes

922
01:38:32,220 --> 01:38:33,220
work against you.

923
01:38:33,220 --> 01:38:34,220
Michelle Duffy, a professor at the University
of Minnesota, did a study of police officers

924
01:38:34,220 --> 01:38:35,220
and how they felt supported, or not, by the
officer that they worked with. Not surprisingly,

925
01:38:35,220 --> 01:38:36,220
negative relationships led to stress. When
officers felt they weren't supported by the

926
01:38:36,220 --> 01:38:37,220
officer they worked with, they didn't work
so hard and took more time off of work.

927
01:38:37,220 --> 01:38:38,220
But what happened when the police officer
felt supported by the other officer for some

928
01:38:38,220 --> 01:38:39,220
of the time? Things didn't get better; they
got worse. Negative relationships aren't good,

929
01:38:39,220 --> 01:38:40,220
but at least you know what is going to happen,
and you can be ready for it. But when you

930
01:38:40,220 --> 01:38:41,220
don't know whether someone will support you
or not, your stress increases. In another

931
01:38:41,220 --> 01:38:42,220
study, Bert Uchino found that "frenemy" relationships
like this were unhealthier than bad relationships.

932
01:38:42,220 --> 01:38:43,220
People with a lot of relationships that were
neither friends nor enemies had higher stress,

933
01:38:43,220 --> 01:38:44,220
were unhappier, and found life more difficult
than other people.

934
01:38:44,220 --> 01:38:45,220
We may feel it is better to keep away from
our enemies and to try to improve our relationship

935
01:38:45,220 --> 01:38:46,220
with frenemies. But that is probably not the
best idea. It's better to keep away from frenemies

936
01:38:46,220 --> 01:38:47,220
and try to turn enemies into friends. Very
often, the best supporters we have are people

937
01:38:47,220 --> 01:38:48,220
who didn't support us in the past, but who
have now come over to our side.

938
01:38:48,220 --> 01:38:49,220
First, when someone has always supported us,
we expect it and don't think it is that wonderful.

939
01:38:49,220 --> 01:38:50,220
But, when someone who didn't support us starts
to become a friend, we like them even more.

940
01:38:50,220 --> 01:38:51,220
Second, they will feel the same about us.
They've worked hard to beat their negative

941
01:38:51,220 --> 01:38:52,220
feelings about us, and now they feel much
more positively toward us.

942
01:38:52,220 --> 01:38:53,220
Third, and most important, our old enemies
are the best at persuading other people to

943
01:38:53,220 --> 01:38:54,220
join our movement. They felt negatively about
our ideas before, so they understand the people

944
01:38:54,220 --> 01:38:55,220
who still feel negatively. And they know why
they changed their minds, so they can explain

945
01:38:55,220 --> 01:38:56,220
this to others. People will listen to them
because they know they weren't always our

946
01:38:56,220 --> 01:38:57,220
friends.

947
01:38:57,220 --> 01:38:58,220
When Lucy Stone, who was working for both
women's suffrage and African-American suffrage,

948
01:38:58,220 --> 01:38:59,220
walked around towns putting up posters for
meetings, young men often followed her, pulling

949
01:38:59,220 --> 01:39:00,220
the posters down. Stone asked them if they
loved their mothers. Of course. Did they love

950
01:39:00,220 --> 01:39:01,220
their sisters? Certainly. She then explained
that in the south of the United States, African-

951
01:39:01,220 --> 01:39:02,220
American men of their age were sold and would
never see their families again. She then invited

952
01:39:02,220 --> 01:39:03,220
the young men to her meetings as her special
guests. Some of these men helped her, and

953
01:39:03,220 --> 01:39:04,220
they were very useful when other young men
started to make trouble.

954
01:39:04,220 --> 01:39:05,220
From unknown to known

955
01:39:05,220 --> 01:39:06,220
In the 1990s, a group of writers suggested
something that had never been done at Disney.

956
01:39:06,220 --> 01:39:07,220
Instead of the old stories like Cinderella
and Snow White, they wanted to write something

957
01:39:07,220 --> 01:39:08,220
completely new. Nobody at Disney really thought
it was a good idea.

958
01:39:08,220 --> 01:39:09,220
The story became The Lion Lang, the most successful
film of 1994, winning two Oscars and a Golden

959
01:39:09,220 --> 01:39:10,220
Globe. Disney hoped the film would make 50
million dollars. By 2014, it had made more

960
01:39:10,220 --> 01:39:11,220
than 1 billion dollars.

961
01:39:11,220 --> 01:39:12,220
Early in the project, five of the writers
had a meeting with Disney management, where

962
01:39:12,220 --> 01:39:13,220
they explained their story about lions. Michael
Eisner, Disney CEO (Chief Executive Officer),

963
01:39:13,220 --> 01:39:14,220
tried to find something he could understand
in it. "Could you make this into Shakespeare's

964
01:39:14,220 --> 01:39:15,220
King Lear?" he asked.

965
01:39:15,220 --> 01:39:16,220
That wasn't really possible. But then, from
the back of the room, Maureen Donley said,

966
01:39:16,220 --> 01:39:17,220
"No, this is Hamlet." Suddenly, everyone understood.
The uncle kills the father, and then the son

967
01:39:17,220 --> 01:39:18,220
has to kill his uncle. So the film became
Hamlet with lions, and Disney decided to make

968
01:39:18,220 --> 01:39:19,220
it.

969
01:39:19,220 --> 01:39:20,220
Justin Berg, a professor at Stanford University,
has explained that the writers had to start

970
01:39:20,220 --> 01:39:21,220
with the lions. If they had started with Hamlet,
the story would have been too much like Shakespeare's.

971
01:39:21,220 --> 01:39:22,220
Beginning in a different place, with lions,
made the story more original, but it provided

972
01:39:22,220 --> 01:39:23,220
other difficulties. With a completely original
story, people very easily get lost. After

973
01:39:23,220 --> 01:39:24,220
starting with the original lions, the writers
found that Hamlet could help them a lot. For

974
01:39:24,220 --> 01:39:25,220
example, they realized that they needed Simba
to think about his future, as Hamlet does

975
01:39:25,220 --> 01:39:26,220
in his "to be or not to be" speech, so they
wrote a new conversation in the film, where

976
01:39:26,220 --> 01:39:27,220
Rafiki tells Simba that he must remember where
he comes from.

977
01:39:27,220 --> 01:39:28,220
Creating coalitions

978
01:39:28,220 --> 01:39:29,220
Frances Willard became leader of the WCTU
after the group began working with the women's

979
01:39:29,220 --> 01:39:30,220
suffrage groups. How could she link women's
suffrage to the problems of alcohol, which

980
01:39:30,220 --> 01:39:31,220
were the WCTU's first interest?

981
01:39:31,220 --> 01:39:32,220
Willard didn't talk about suffrage, but about
home protection. The idea of home protection

982
01:39:32,220 --> 01:39:33,220
was central to many women, especially religious
women. Willard used religion a lot in her

983
01:39:33,220 --> 01:39:34,220
speeches, and the WCTU supporters liked that.
But she also explained that women's suffrage

984
01:39:34,220 --> 01:39:35,220
was the best way of protecting women from
men drinking alcohol and being violent.

985
01:39:35,220 --> 01:39:36,220
To return to the Goldilocks idea again, the
idea of women having the right to vote was

986
01:39:36,220 --> 01:39:37,220
"too hot" for some people. The idea of home
protection was "too cold" for others. But,

987
01:39:37,220 --> 01:39:38,220
when women's leaders explained how women could
make things better for everybody, things were

988
01:39:38,220 --> 01:39:39,220
neither too hot nor too cold, and soon women
achieved the right to vote in a number of

989
01:39:39,220 --> 01:39:40,220
states.

990
01:39:40,220 --> 01:39:41,220
After twenty years of fighting, the two women's
suffrage organizations wanted to work together

991
01:39:41,220 --> 01:39:42,220
again. But it was very difficult for Stone
to work with Anthony; they had been fighting

992
01:39:42,220 --> 01:39:43,220
for years, and the relationship was broken.
After three years, in 1890, Stone realized

993
01:39:43,220 --> 01:39:44,220
it was impossible. She asked her daughter
and her daughter's husband to take on the

994
01:39:44,220 --> 01:39:45,220
job, and the two organizations did come together.

995
01:39:45,220 --> 01:39:46,220
When Lucy Stone was dying, in 1893, she whispered
to her daughter: "Make the world better."

996
01:39:46,220 --> 01:39:47,220
It took another twenty-seven years before
women's suffrage was achieved in the United

997
01:39:47,220 --> 01:39:48,220
States, in 1920, but Stone had done a lot
of the early work toward it.

998
