A few seconds ago, he was standing calmly
on third base. Now his feet are dancing. He

1000
01:39:50,220 --> 01:39:51,220
is ready to run to home base.

1001
01:39:51,220 --> 01:39:52,220
He has been here before. He is one of the
greatest players ever to play baseball. Four

1002
01:39:52,220 --> 01:39:53,220
times, he has led his team to the World Series,
and all four times, they have lost to the

1003
01:39:53,220 --> 01:39:54,220
Yankees. Now his team is down 6 - 4 in the
eighth inning. Is it time to try to steal

1004
01:39:54,220 --> 01:39:55,220
home?

1005
01:39:55,220 --> 01:39:56,220
Stealing a base is one of the riskiest moves
in baseball. It increases your team's chances

1006
01:39:56,220 --> 01:39:57,220
of scoring by only 3 percent, and to do it
successfully you have to slide into the base

1007
01:39:57,220 --> 01:39:58,220
at high speed, and there is a good chance
you will hurt yourself. Stealing home base

1008
01:39:58,220 --> 01:39:59,220
is even riskier than stealing other bases,
because the pitcher can see you and he has

1009
01:39:59,220 --> 01:40:00,220
an easy throw. The pitcher has to throw the
ball 60 feet; you have to run 90 feet, so

1010
01:40:00,220 --> 01:40:01,220
you have to run faster than the ball. And
your chances of getting hurt when you are

1011
01:40:01,220 --> 01:40:02,220
running to home base are four times higher.
In the whole of the 2012 season, only three

1012
01:40:02,220 --> 01:40:03,220
players tried to steal home.

1013
01:40:03,220 --> 01:40:04,220
This man, though, is different. He has stolen
home base more than any other player of the

1014
01:40:04,220 --> 01:40:05,220
day - nineteen times. In 100 years, only two
other players have managed more than nine.

1015
01:40:05,220 --> 01:40:06,220
But if you think stealing base is about speed,
think again. He's thirty-six now, no longer

1016
01:40:06,220 --> 01:40:07,220
a young man. He's been injured for part of
the season. Six years ago, he stole thirty-seven

1017
01:40:07,220 --> 01:40:08,220
bases in a season, but he has stolen far fewer
in the last two seasons. His hair is silver,

1018
01:40:08,220 --> 01:40:09,220
and he weighs more than he used to. This will
be his last season.

1019
01:40:09,220 --> 01:40:10,220
But this man has spent his life taking action
when others stood and watched, and he's not

1020
01:40:10,220 --> 01:40:11,220
going to stop now. He waits for the right
time and then runs. He slides into home base

1021
01:40:11,220 --> 01:40:12,220
just in time.

1022
01:40:12,220 --> 01:40:13,220
It's too little, too late. His team loses
the first game to the Yankees. But the effect

1023
01:40:13,220 --> 01:40:14,220
on the team is enormous. They are on fire
for the rest of the season and go on to win.

1024
01:40:14,220 --> 01:40:15,220
Years later, a journalist said that this man's
attempts to steal home base were the second-bravest

1025
01:40:15,220 --> 01:40:16,220
thing he had ever done.

1026
01:40:16,220 --> 01:40:17,220
The first was becoming Major League Baseball's
first black player, in 1947.

1027
01:40:17,220 --> 01:40:18,220
To become original we need to take some risks.
We can never be sure that we will succeed.

1028
01:40:18,220 --> 01:40:19,220
As journalist, Robert Quillen wrote in 1924,
"Progress always involves risk. You can't

1029
01:40:19,220 --> 01:40:20,220
steal second and keep one foot on first base."

1030
01:40:20,220 --> 01:40:21,220
From the start, Jackie Robinson had to deal
with white players who refused to play with

1031
01:40:21,220 --> 01:40:22,220
or against him, as well as hate mail. What
made him so brave? We can begin to find the

1032
01:40:22,220 --> 01:40:23,220
answer by looking at the families of players
who are good at stealing bases. Since 1962,

1033
01:40:23,220 --> 01:40:24,220
only ten players have stolen at least seventy
bases in two different seasons. Do you see

1034
01:40:24,220 --> 01:40:25,220
anything interesting here? Look at the table
on the next page.

1035
01:40:25,220 --> 01:40:26,220
Trying to find out why some baseball players
steal more bases than other players, Frank

1036
01:40:26,220 --> 01:40:27,220
Sulloway and Richard Zweigenhaft found more
than 400 men who played professional baseball.

1037
01:40:27,220 --> 01:40:28,220
Then they found something surprising. Birth
order can tell you which man will try to steal

1038
01:40:28,220 --> 01:40:29,220
most bases. Younger brothers were 10.6 times
more likely than older brothers to try to

1039
01:40:29,220 --> 01:40:30,220
steal.

1040
01:40:30,220 --> 01:40:31,220
Younger brothers weren't better players in
other ways. The big difference was in how

1041
01:40:31,220 --> 01:40:32,220
often they took risks. And they didn't just
take more risks; they were 3.2 times more

1042
01:40:32,220 --> 01:40:33,220
likely to steal a base safely.

1043
01:40:33,220 --> 01:40:34,220
The desire to take risks actually means that
younger brothers are less likely to play baseball.

1044
01:40:34,220 --> 01:40:35,220
Across twenty-four studies of more than 8,000
people, younger brothers and sisters were

1045
01:40:35,220 --> 01:40:36,220
1.48 times more likely to choose sports where
there are more injuries, such as football,

1046
01:40:36,220 --> 01:40:37,220
rugby, diving, skiing, and car racing. Older
brothers and sisters preferred safer sports:

1047
01:40:37,220 --> 01:40:38,220
baseball, golf, tennis, rowing, and cycling.

1048
01:40:38,220 --> 01:40:39,220
If we look at the three players who have stolen
the most bases, Jackie Robinson was the youngest

1049
01:40:39,220 --> 01:40:40,220
of five children. Rod Carew, who comes second
in the number of steals, is fourth of five

1050
01:40:40,220 --> 01:40:41,220
children. And third is Paul Molitor, who is
the fourth child of eight.

1051
01:40:41,220 --> 01:40:42,220
Younger children are not just risk-takers
in baseball. There are differences in politics

1052
01:40:42,220 --> 01:40:43,220
and science, too. Sulloway researched nearly
4,000 scientists to see what they had said

1053
01:40:43,220 --> 01:40:44,220
when revolutionary ideas appeared. He looked
at the ideas of major scientists such as Copernicus,

1054
01:40:44,220 --> 01:40:45,220
Darwin, Newton, and Einstein, and he researched
what 4,000 other scientists had written at

1055
01:40:45,220 --> 01:40:46,220
the time. Had they supported these revolutionary
ideas or not?

1056
01:40:46,220 --> 01:40:47,220
Compared to firstborn children, scientists
who were younger children were three times

1057
01:40:47,220 --> 01:40:48,220
more likely to support Newton and Einstein
at the time when their theories were revolutionary.

1058
01:40:48,220 --> 01:40:49,220
In the fifty years after Copernicus published
his idea that the earth went around the sun,

1059
01:40:49,220 --> 01:40:50,220
scientists who were younger children were
5.4 times more likely to support Copernicus'

1060
01:40:50,220 --> 01:40:51,220
ideas than firstborn scientists.

1061
01:40:51,220 --> 01:40:52,220
We often expect that younger scientists are
more likely to support new ideas. But Sulloway

1062
01:40:52,220 --> 01:40:53,220
shows that birth order is actually more important
than age.

1063
01:40:53,220 --> 01:40:54,220
As a firstborn myself, I was a little upset
by this research. But, as I learned more,

1064
01:40:54,220 --> 01:40:55,220
I realized that the effects of birth order
can be avoided. By bringing up all children

1065
01:40:55,220 --> 01:40:56,220
in a similar way to younger children, we can
raise any child to be more original.

1066
01:40:56,220 --> 01:40:57,220
This chapter looks at how the family affects
originality. What is special about being a

1067
01:40:57,220 --> 01:40:58,220
younger child does family size matter, and
how can this affect the way we raise our children?

1068
01:40:58,220 --> 01:40:59,220
I'll use birth order as a way of looking at
the effect family has on how likely we are

1069
01:40:59,220 --> 01:41:00,220
to take risks. To see how brothers and sisters
are more different than we expect, we'll look

1070
01:41:00,220 --> 01:41:01,220
at how Jackie Robinson was raised, and also
at the early years of some of the greatest

1071
01:41:01,220 --> 01:41:02,220
comedy stars in America. You'll also find
out how parents congratulate children in the

1072
01:41:02,220 --> 01:41:03,220
wrong way and how reading stories can help
originality.

1073
01:41:03,220 --> 01:41:04,220
Born to be a rebel

1074
01:41:04,220 --> 01:41:05,220
One day in 1944, when he was still in the
army, Jackie Robinson refused to sit at the

1075
01:41:05,220 --> 01:41:06,220
back of a bus with other African Americans.
The driver "shouted that if I didn't move

1076
01:41:06,220 --> 01:41:07,220
to the (back) of the bus he would cause me
plenty of trouble," Robinson remembered. Robinson

1077
01:41:07,220 --> 01:41:08,220
told the driver he couldn't care less about
the driver causing him trouble. When Robinson

1078
01:41:08,220 --> 01:41:09,220
talked about his attempt to steal home base
in the World Series, he used similar language.

1079
01:41:09,220 --> 01:41:10,220
"I just took off and did it. I really didn't
care whether I made it or not."

1080
01:41:10,220 --> 01:41:11,220
"I really didn't care," tells us something
important about Jackie Robinson and what he

1081
01:41:11,220 --> 01:41:12,220
had learned about risk. Many people, when
they are deciding what to do, think about

1082
01:41:12,220 --> 01:41:13,220
how to get the best results. But someone like
Robinson thinks differently. What is the right

1083
01:41:13,220 --> 01:41:14,220
thing for someone like me to do? These people
don't look at other people. They decide by

1084
01:41:14,220 --> 01:41:15,220
looking at themselves. The first group of
people, who think about the results and what

1085
01:41:15,220 --> 01:41:16,220
other people will think, can always find a
reason not to take a risk. And this sort of

1086
01:41:16,220 --> 01:41:17,220
decision can be decided by birth order.

1087
01:41:17,220 --> 01:41:18,220
For many years, experts have argued that it
is helpful to be firstborn. When he or she

1088
01:41:18,220 --> 01:41:19,220
is born, the first child doesn't have to share
parents with brothers or sisters and gets

1089
01:41:19,220 --> 01:41:20,220
a lot more of their parents' time. Firstborns
are more likely to win a Nobel Prize for science,

1090
01:41:20,220 --> 01:41:21,220
or to get into the United States Congress.
Research into 1,500 CEOs shows that 43 percent

1091
01:41:21,220 --> 01:41:22,220
of them were firstborn.

1092
01:41:22,220 --> 01:41:23,220
In Europe, it was shown that firstborns earn
salaries that are 14 percent higher than their

1093
01:41:23,220 --> 01:41:24,220
younger brothers and sisters when they start
work. But the situation changes by the time

1094
01:41:24,220 --> 01:41:25,220
they reach the age of thirty. The salaries
of those born later grow faster because they

1095
01:41:25,220 --> 01:41:26,220
are willing to change jobs sooner and more
often. Firstborns avoid risk more than those

1096
01:41:26,220 --> 01:41:27,220
born after them. Those born later are more
likely to drink or smoke, and they are less

1097
01:41:27,220 --> 01:41:28,220
likely to have good insurance.

1098
01:41:28,220 --> 01:41:29,220
Although many people now think that birth
order has some effect, the science of birth

1099
01:41:29,220 --> 01:41:30,220
order has many critics. Birth order doesn't
fix you in any way, it only affects the direction

1100
01:41:30,220 --> 01:41:31,220
in which you will probably develop. There
are a lot of other things that can affect

1101
01:41:31,220 --> 01:41:32,220
you. It's difficult for research to look at
birth order on its own; there are too many

1102
01:41:32,220 --> 01:41:33,220
other things that can affect development.
But when I looked at birth order I discovered

1103
01:41:33,220 --> 01:41:34,220
that it was a better way of deciding whether
a person would be a risk-taker than I had

1104
01:41:34,220 --> 01:41:35,220
expected.

1105
01:41:35,220 --> 01:41:36,220
In one study, people scored their brothers
and sisters and themselves on school achievement

1106
01:41:36,220 --> 01:41:37,220
and on whether they were rebels or not. A
rebel is someone who doesn't accept the default.

1107
01:41:37,220 --> 01:41:38,220
People with high school achievement were 2.3
times more likely to be born first than last.

1108
01:41:38,220 --> 01:41:39,220
Rebels were twice as likely to be born last
than first. There are two possible ways to

1109
01:41:39,220 --> 01:41:40,220
explain the risk-taking in those born later.
One is about how children deal with arguments

1110
01:41:40,220 --> 01:41:41,220
with their brothers and sisters. The other
is about how parents raise younger children

1111
01:41:41,220 --> 01:41:42,220
differently. Although we can't control birth
order, we can change some of its effects.

1112
01:41:42,220 --> 01:41:43,220
Niche picking

1113
01:41:43,220 --> 01:41:44,220
Look at a lot of brothers and sisters and
you will see the big differences in personality

1114
01:41:44,220 --> 01:41:45,220
aren't between families, but between children
in families. As adults, brothers and sisters

1115
01:41:45,220 --> 01:41:46,220
from the same family are different in how
much risk they want to take, or how much they

1116
01:41:46,220 --> 01:41:47,220
rebel, even though they have been raised by
the same parents.

1117
01:41:47,220 --> 01:41:48,220
Niche picking may help to explain this. The
idea was developed by Alfred Adler, who thought

1118
01:41:48,220 --> 01:41:49,220
that Sigmund Freud's theories about parents
didn't explain the part that brothers and

1119
01:41:49,220 --> 01:41:50,220
sisters play in the development of one another's
personality. Adler suggested that because

1120
01:41:50,220 --> 01:41:51,220
firstborn children start life as only children
they learn from their parents. When second

1121
01:41:51,220 --> 01:41:52,220
or third children come along, the first child
risks losing its first place, so may decide

1122
01:41:52,220 --> 01:41:53,220
to take on the job of being a parent and give
orders to the younger child. The younger child

1123
01:41:53,220 --> 01:41:54,220
answers this by becoming a rebel.

1124
01:41:54,220 --> 01:41:55,220
It can be difficult to compete with an older
brother or sister, so the younger child has

1125
01:41:55,220 --> 01:41:56,220
to choose a different path. The niche of the
responsible academic achiever is often taken

1126
01:41:56,220 --> 01:41:57,220
by the first child. Once the first child has
taken this niche, it can be difficult for

1127
01:41:57,220 --> 01:41:58,220
the next to compete. This depends on the age
difference; if it's only one year, the younger

1128
01:41:58,220 --> 01:41:59,220
child may be able to compete. And if it's
seven years, the niche may be open again.

1129
01:41:59,220 --> 01:42:00,220
In baseball, brothers who were between two
and five years apart were more likely to play

1130
01:42:00,220 --> 01:42:01,220
in different positions than brothers who were
less than two or more than five years apart.

1131
01:42:01,220 --> 01:42:02,220
Jackie Robinson was a runner at college, but
he couldn't compete with his older brother

1132
01:42:02,220 --> 01:42:03,220
Mack, who was five years older and won a silver
medal at the 1936 Olympic Games. Jackie Robinson

1133
01:42:03,220 --> 01:42:04,220
changed to basketball, football, and then
baseball.

1134
01:42:04,220 --> 01:42:05,220
Outside of the world of sports, I decided
to look at comedy. Comedy seems like a risky

1135
01:42:05,220 --> 01:42:06,220
job, so we would expect younger children to
be more successful. I looked at a 2004 list

1136
01:42:06,220 --> 01:42:07,220
of the 100 greatest comedy performers. You
would expect an equal number of any group

1137
01:42:07,220 --> 01:42:08,220
of 100 to be born first, or born last. However,
when I looked at these 100 people, forty-four

1138
01:42:08,220 --> 01:42:09,220
of them were born last, while only twenty
were born first. They came from families with

1139
01:42:09,220 --> 01:42:10,220
an average of 3.5 children, but nearly half
were the baby of their families.

1140
01:42:10,220 --> 01:42:11,220
When I looked at particular performers, I
found that their older brothers and sisters

1141
01:42:11,220 --> 01:42:12,220
were often responsible achievers. For example,
Chelsea Handler's five older brothers and

1142
01:42:12,220 --> 01:42:13,220
sisters are an engineer, a chef, an accountant,
a lawyer, and a nurse.

1143
01:42:13,220 --> 01:42:14,220
Niche picking shows how younger children often
try to be different from their older brothers

1144
01:42:14,220 --> 01:42:15,220
and sisters. Parents may try to give each
child the same experience, but birth order

1145
01:42:15,220 --> 01:42:16,220
pushes their personalities in different directions.

1146
01:42:16,220 --> 01:42:17,220
Less responsibility

1147
01:42:17,220 --> 01:42:18,220
If Jackie Robinson had been a first child,
he would have been raised mainly by his mother.

1148
01:42:18,220 --> 01:42:19,220
But, with five children to feed, Mrs. Robinson
needed to work. Robinson's older sister, Willa

1149
01:42:19,220 --> 01:42:20,220
Mae, washed him, dressed him, and fed him.
And when she went to school, she took her

1150
01:42:20,220 --> 01:42:21,220
baby brother with her, and he played outside
of the classroom. And, if he got into fights,

1151
01:42:21,220 --> 01:42:22,220
his older brother Frank was there to defend
him. When older brothers and sisters behave

1152
01:42:22,220 --> 01:42:23,220
like parents, there aren't as many rules or
punishments, and younger children take risks

1153
01:42:23,220 --> 01:42:24,220
earlier.

1154
01:42:24,220 --> 01:42:25,220
Parents often become more relaxed with the
younger children, and things are not so strict.

1155
01:42:25,220 --> 01:42:26,220
And as the older children take on more responsibilities,
there is less need for the younger child to

1156
01:42:26,220 --> 01:42:27,220
be responsible. The larger the family, the
more the younger children can escape responsibility.

1157
01:42:27,220 --> 01:42:28,220
We can explain the risk-taking of many originals
by their position in the family and the fact

1158
01:42:28,220 --> 01:42:29,220
that this gives them more freedom and allows
them to be rebels. But parents can encourage

1159
01:42:29,220 --> 01:42:30,220
children to be original whether they are the
first or the last. But one of the dangers

1160
01:42:30,220 --> 01:42:31,220
of originality is that being a rebel is not
always positive; it can also be negative.

1161
01:42:31,220 --> 01:42:32,220
Some research into how parents deal with good
or bad behavior will be helpful here.

1162
01:42:32,220 --> 01:42:33,220
Explaining and correcting

1163
01:42:33,220 --> 01:42:34,220
Some years ago, researchers found that, between
the ages of two and ten, parents ask their

1164
01:42:34,220 --> 01:42:35,220
children to change their behavior once every
six to nine minutes. This means perhaps fifty

1165
01:42:35,220 --> 01:42:36,220
times a day, or more than 15,000 times a year.

1166
01:42:36,220 --> 01:42:37,220
For their Altruistic Personality Study, Samuel
and Pearl Oliner studied people who had taken

1167
01:42:37,220 --> 01:42:38,220
great risks to save Jews during the Holocaust
between 1940 and 1945, when 6 million Jews

1168
01:42:38,220 --> 01:42:39,220
were murdered. They discovered there was a
difference in how parents had corrected the

1169
01:42:39,220 --> 01:42:40,220
mistakes of those risk-takers when they were
children. Their parents explained why they

1170
01:42:40,220 --> 01:42:41,220
were correcting them 21 percent of the time,
compared to 6 percent of the time for other

1171
01:42:41,220 --> 01:42:42,220
parents. One interviewee said that her mother
"told me when I did something wrong... She

1172
01:42:42,220 --> 01:42:43,220
tried to make me understand with my mind what
I'd done wrong." The Oliners also found that

1173
01:42:43,220 --> 01:42:44,220
explaining was especially useful when it made
children think what would happen to other

1174
01:42:44,220 --> 01:42:45,220
people as a result of their actions.

1175
01:42:45,220 --> 01:42:46,220
This can also work with adults. In hospitals,
to encourage doctors and nurses to wash their

1176
01:42:46,220 --> 01:42:47,220
hands more often, David Hofmann and I put
two different signs next to soap machines.

1177
01:42:47,220 --> 01:42:48,220
Over the next two weeks, we counted the number
of times doctors and nurses washed their hands,

1178
01:42:48,220 --> 01:42:49,220
before and after seeing a patient. The sign
on the left made no difference. But the sign

1179
01:42:49,220 --> 01:42:50,220
on the right made a big difference: using
the word "patients" instead of "you" resulted

1180
01:42:50,220 --> 01:42:51,220
in 10 percent more hand washing and 45 percent
more soap being used. Thinking about other

1181
01:42:51,220 --> 01:42:52,220
people changed doctors and nurses behavior
more than thinking about themselves.

1182
01:42:52,220 --> 01:42:53,220
Behavior and character

1183
01:42:53,220 --> 01:42:54,220
Good behavior is encouraged partly by what
parents say after a child has done the right

1184
01:42:54,220 --> 01:42:55,220
thing. The last time you saw a child doing
something good, you probably talked about

1185
01:42:55,220 --> 01:42:56,220
what they had done. "That was so sweet." By
talking about their behavior, you encourage

1186
01:42:56,220 --> 01:42:57,220
them to do it again. But Joan Grusec did an
interesting experiment about this. After some

1187
01:42:57,220 --> 01:42:58,220
children shared toys with other children,
some of them had their behavior mentioned

1188
01:42:58,220 --> 01:42:59,220
in feedback: "It was nice of you to share
those toys with other children. That was a

1189
01:42:59,220 --> 01:43:00,220
nice and helpful thing to do." Others were
given feedback on their characters: "I guess

1190
01:43:00,220 --> 01:43:01,220
you are the kind of person who likes to help
others. You are a helpful person."

1191
01:43:01,220 --> 01:43:02,220
Later, in a similar situation, the children
who had received character comments were 45

1192
01:43:02,220 --> 01:43:03,220
percent more likely to share toys, while those
who received behavior comments were only 10

1193
01:43:03,220 --> 01:43:04,220
percent more likely to share. When our character
is mentioned, we begin to build up an idea

1194
01:43:04,220 --> 01:43:05,220
of ourselves as a good person.

1195
01:43:05,220 --> 01:43:06,220
It has been suggested that the message "Don't
drink and drive" might be better if it were

1196
01:43:06,220 --> 01:43:07,220
changed to "Don't be a drunk driver." The
same idea can be used for originality. When

1197
01:43:07,220 --> 01:43:08,220
a child produces a good painting, rather than
saying that their work is creative we could

1198
01:43:08,220 --> 01:43:09,220
say, "You are creative." When we move from
talking about behavior to talking about character,

1199
01:43:09,220 --> 01:43:10,220
people think differently.

1200
01:43:10,220 --> 01:43:11,220
Why parents aren't the best role models

1201
01:43:11,220 --> 01:43:12,220
We can give children quite a lot of freedom
if we explain how what they do affects other

1202
01:43:12,220 --> 01:43:13,220
people. They will be more likely to be original
in a positive way, rather than a negative

1203
01:43:13,220 --> 01:43:14,220
one. But, as they grow up, they often don't
aim high enough.

1204
01:43:14,220 --> 01:43:15,220
Parents can begin the development of originality
in their children, but as children get older,

1205
01:43:15,220 --> 01:43:16,220
they need role models people who have been
original in their own area of work. Jackie

1206
01:43:16,220 --> 01:43:17,220
Robinson, for example, found a role model
in a young mechanic. As a boy, there was a

1207
01:43:17,220 --> 01:43:18,220
danger that Robinson would become a member
of a criminal gang, but this mechanic explained

1208
01:43:18,220 --> 01:43:19,220
to Robinson that he was hurting his mother.
Martin Luther King, Jr. had Gandhi as a role

1209
01:43:19,220 --> 01:43:20,220
model, as did Nelson Mandela.

1210
01:43:20,220 --> 01:43:21,220
Some originals have found role models in fiction.
For example, Sheryl Sandberg and Jeff Bezos

1211
01:43:21,220 --> 01:43:22,220
have both mentioned finding a role model in
the book A Wrinkle in Time, in which a young

1212
01:43:22,220 --> 01:43:23,220
girl learns to bend the laws of physics and
travel through time. There are studies that

1213
01:43:23,220 --> 01:43:24,220
show that, when children's stories show original
achievements, people innovate more twenty

1214
01:43:24,220 --> 01:43:25,220
to forty years later. In one study, psychologists
noted that original achievement increased

1215
01:43:25,220 --> 01:43:26,220
in American children's books by 66 percent
between 1810 and 1850. Between 1850 and 1890,

1216
01:43:26,220 --> 01:43:27,220
the number of patents increased by 700 percent.
Children's books reflected popular values

1217
01:43:27,220 --> 01:43:28,220
at the time but also helped to create values.
It takes time for children to learn originality

1218
01:43:28,220 --> 01:43:29,220
from characters in fiction. We can be sure
that the next group of originals will have

1219
01:43:29,220 --> 01:43:30,220
been affected by Harry Potter, books where
there is a lot of original achievement. When

1220
01:43:30,220 --> 01:43:31,220
children read about heroes who are also originals,
it may change the way they pick their niches

1221
01:43:31,220 --> 01:43:32,220
in the family. Wherever we are in family birth
order, there are niches for us, and role models

1222
01:43:32,220 --> 01:43:33,220
for originality.

1223
01:43:33,220 --> 01:43:34,220
CHAPTER SEVEN
Groupthink

1224
01:43:34,220 --> 01:43:35,220
Standing on stage in front of his audience,
a technology inventor pulled something out

1225
01:43:35,220 --> 01:43:36,220
of his pocket. It was so much smaller than
competing products that nobody in the room

1226
01:43:36,220 --> 01:43:37,220
could believe it. He was a man known for his
originality and creativity, and he didn't

1227
01:43:37,220 --> 01:43:38,220
believe in market research. He said his company
makes products that people do not even know

1228
01:43:38,220 --> 01:43:39,220
they want. This man made his company great,
only to be forced out, and then watch his

1229
01:43:39,220 --> 01:43:40,220
company disappear.

1230
01:43:40,220 --> 01:43:41,220
The story seems to describe Steve Jobs, but
actually, this man was one of Jobs' heroes:

1231
01:43:41,220 --> 01:43:42,220
Edwin Land, the man behind Polaroid. Today,
Land is remembered for inventing the instant

1232
01:43:42,220 --> 01:43:43,220
camera. But Land also invented something much
more important: the light filter that is used

1233
01:43:43,220 --> 01:43:44,220
in billions of products, from sunglasses to
watches. Land was responsible for 535 patents,

1234
01:43:44,220 --> 01:43:45,220
more than any American before him except for
Thomas Edison.

1235
01:43:45,220 --> 01:43:46,220
Land was certainly a great original, but his
company did not encourage originality. Polaroid

1236
01:43:46,220 --> 01:43:47,220
was one of the companies that started work
on the digital camera, but in the end, the

1237
01:43:47,220 --> 01:43:48,220
company failed because of it. Polaroid's engineers
had a high-quality digital camera ready in

1238
01:43:48,220 --> 01:43:49,220
1992, but the inventors couldn't persuade
the company to start selling it until 1996.

1239
01:43:49,220 --> 01:43:50,220
By then, there were more than forty other
digital cameras on the market.

1240
01:43:50,220 --> 01:43:51,220
Polaroid made a basic mistake. Within the
company, many people thought that customers

1241
01:43:51,220 --> 01:43:52,220
would always want to have printed pictures,
and the important people in the organization

1242
01:43:52,220 --> 01:43:53,220
didn't question this idea. It was a case of
groupthink - the desire to reach agreement

1243
01:43:53,220 --> 01:43:54,220
instead of allowing disagreement. Groupthink
is the enemy of originality.

1244
01:43:54,220 --> 01:43:55,220
In a famous study, the psychologist Irving
Janis argued that many bad decisions made

1245
01:43:55,220 --> 01:43:56,220
by the United States government were caused
by groupthink. Janis believed that groupthink

1246
01:43:56,220 --> 01:43:57,220
occurred when people felt they were deeply
involved in a group and they wanted to agree

1247
01:43:57,220 --> 01:43:58,220
with the group, instead of suggesting different
ideas. He said that it was the safe, friendly

1248
01:43:58,220 --> 01:43:59,220
feelings inside a close group that created
groupthink.

1249
01:43:59,220 --> 01:44:00,220
People accepted Janis' theory for a long time,
but it isn't true. Janis did his work in 1973,

1250
01:44:00,220 --> 01:44:01,220
but researchers now have seen a lot more government
documents, and it's clear that these bad decisions

1251
01:44:01,220 --> 01:44:02,220
were not made by one small, close group. And
there was another problem with Janis' theory.

1252
01:44:02,220 --> 01:44:03,220
Most of the time he looked at groups making
bad decisions. But how do we know that it

1253
01:44:03,220 --> 01:44:04,220
was actually the closeness of the group that
caused the bad decisions? Janis needed to

1254
01:44:04,220 --> 01:44:05,220
compare good and bad decisions to see whether
close groups are more likely to make decisions

1255
01:44:05,220 --> 01:44:06,220
through groupthink.

1256
01:44:06,220 --> 01:44:07,220
The theory of close groups causing groupthink
isn't true in business either. When researchers

1257
01:44:07,220 --> 01:44:08,220
looked at successful and failed decisions
in management teams at seven major companies,

1258
01:44:08,220 --> 01:44:09,220
they discovered that close groups weren't
more likely to want to agree with each other

1259
01:44:09,220 --> 01:44:10,220
and refuse different ideas. In fact, close
groups often made better business decisions.

1260
01:44:10,220 --> 01:44:11,220
The same was true in politics.

1261
01:44:11,220 --> 01:44:12,220
In this chapter, I want to look at what really
causes groupthink and what we can do to prevent

1262
01:44:12,220 --> 01:44:13,220
it. Why do some close groups make bad decisions
while others make good ones? I want to see

1263
01:44:13,220 --> 01:44:14,220
how to fight groupthink and allow original
opinions. I'll look at Polaroid's mistakes,

1264
01:44:14,220 --> 01:44:15,220
and I'll also examine an organization that
has an interesting new way of avoiding conformity.

1265
01:44:15,220 --> 01:44:16,220
You'll see why people often don't listen to
original ideas, and why it's sometimes better

1266
01:44:16,220 --> 01:44:17,220
to ask people to complain about problems rather
than to solve them. In the end, you'll see

1267
01:44:17,220 --> 01:44:18,220
what ordinary people and organizations can
do to allow originality to develop.

1268
01:44:18,220 --> 01:44:19,220
Commitment to organizations

1269
01:44:19,220 --> 01:44:20,220
In the 1990s, a group of experts led by James
Baron interviewed 200 people who had started

1270
01:44:20,220 --> 01:44:21,220
technology companies in Silicon Valley. They
asked these leaders what sort of organization

1271
01:44:21,220 --> 01:44:22,220
they were trying to develop when they started
out.

1272
01:44:22,220 --> 01:44:23,220
They found three major organizational plans:
professional, star, and commitment. In a professional

1273
01:44:23,220 --> 01:44:24,220
organization, managers tried to hire people
with the right skills - engineers who could

1274
01:44:24,220 --> 01:44:25,220
write in JavaScript or C++, for example. In
a star organization, managers were not so

1275
01:44:25,220 --> 01:44:26,220
interested in skills as in the future; they
looked for the brightest people and didn't

1276
01:44:26,220 --> 01:44:27,220
worry so much about their skills, because
these people would learn quickly.

1277
01:44:27,220 --> 01:44:28,220
In a commitment organization, employees were
hired to fit company culture. Skills and intelligence

1278
01:44:28,220 --> 01:44:29,220
were useful, but the important thing was that
the employee believed in the company. Commitment

1279
01:44:29,220 --> 01:44:30,220
organizations wanted to build strong emotional
links between employees and to the organization.

1280
01:44:30,220 --> 01:44:31,220
They often used words like family and love
when they talked about the company.

1281
01:44:31,220 --> 01:44:32,220
Baron's team wanted to see which type of organization
led to the most success. They followed the

1282
01:44:32,220 --> 01:44:33,220
200 companies through the 1990s, into the
2000s. They discovered that one organizational

1283
01:44:33,220 --> 01:44:34,220
culture was much better than the others: commitment.

1284
01:44:34,220 --> 01:44:35,220
Where a company had a commitment culture,
the number of failures was zero. Not one of

1285
01:44:35,220 --> 01:44:36,220
them went out of business. But the number
of failures for star organizations was high,

1286
01:44:36,220 --> 01:44:37,220
and professional companies did even worse.

1287
01:44:37,220 --> 01:44:38,220
We can see that a commitment culture worked
well in the early days of Polaroid when everybody

1288
01:44:38,220 --> 01:44:39,220
worked hard and there was a desire for originality
and quality. When Edwin Land was developing

1289
01:44:39,220 --> 01:44:40,220
his instant camera, he once worked for eighteen
days without stopping, not even changing his

1290
01:44:40,220 --> 01:44:41,220
clothes. While his competitor, Kodak, hired
scientists, Land looked for a mixed group

1291
01:44:41,220 --> 01:44:42,220
of employees, including women with artistic
experience. Just like the commitment organizations

1292
01:44:42,220 --> 01:44:43,220
in Silicon Valley, he didn't worry about skills
or star qualities. He wanted people who would

1293
01:44:43,220 --> 01:44:44,220
have original ideas and work hard for the
company. His employees developed strong emotional

1294
01:44:44,220 --> 01:44:45,220
links with the company. When you feel like
that, it's hard to imagine working somewhere

1295
01:44:45,220 --> 01:44:46,220
else.

1296
01:44:46,220 --> 01:44:47,220
After the instant camera, Polaroid was responsible
for two other important new developments in

1297
01:44:47,220 --> 01:44:48,220
film technology. The first was the use of
sepia, or brown, photos. Black-and-white instant

1298
01:44:48,220 --> 01:44:49,220
photos often faded, and sepia worked better.
The person who discovered that was Meroe Morse,

1299
01:44:49,220 --> 01:44:50,220
who had been a student of art history and
had not studied either physics or chemistry

1300
01:44:50,220 --> 01:44:51,220
in college. She worked so hard that her laboratory
worked twenty-four hours a day. The second

1301
01:44:51,220 --> 01:44:52,220
new product was instant color photography.
Howard Rogers, who had been a car mechanic,

1302
01:44:52,220 --> 01:44:53,220
worked for fifteen years to solve that problem.

1303
01:44:53,220 --> 01:44:54,220
Problems with growth

1304
01:44:54,220 --> 01:44:55,220
Commitment cultures are very useful at the
beginning of the life of an organization,

1305
01:44:55,220 --> 01:44:56,220
but, over time, things don't usually go so
well. Although these companies grow well at

1306
01:44:56,220 --> 01:44:57,220
first, growth slows down after a time. When
employees share a commitment to the company's

1307
01:44:57,220 --> 01:44:58,220
clear goals, they can work well in a business
situation that they understand. But if things

1308
01:44:58,220 --> 01:44:59,220
keep changing, as they do in the computer
or airline industries, the positive things

1309
01:44:59,220 --> 01:45:00,220
about this strong culture disappear. When
the market is changing, these companies find

1310
01:45:00,220 --> 01:45:01,220
it difficult to look outside of themselves,
and they fail to learn and change.

1311
01:45:01,220 --> 01:45:02,220
This is what happened with Polaroid. After
Land invented the instant camera in 1948,

1312
01:45:02,220 --> 01:45:03,220
the company went from making under 7 million
dollars in 1950 to making 950 million dollars

1313
01:45:03,220 --> 01:45:04,220
in 1976. During this time, there were no big
changes in the industry; customers loved high-quality

1314
01:45:04,220 --> 01:45:05,220
cameras that printed instant pictures. But,
with the development of digital technology,

1315
01:45:05,220 --> 01:45:06,220
the market began to change, and Polaroid's
culture didn't allow the company to move as

1316
01:45:06,220 --> 01:45:07,220
fast as market developments.

1317
01:45:07,220 --> 01:45:08,220
In 1980, Land was contacted by Akio Morita
of Sony who suggested that film was not the

1318
01:45:08,220 --> 01:45:09,220
future and wanted Sony and Polaroid to work
together on an electronic camera. Land wasn't

1319
01:45:09,220 --> 01:45:10,220
interested. He thought only about the chemistry
and physics in photography and didn't believe

1320
01:45:10,220 --> 01:45:11,220
digital photos would ever be good enough.
As Polaroid began to have difficulties, Land

1321
01:45:11,220 --> 01:45:12,220
didn't look outside of his organization. Instead,
he worked only with his supporters inside

1322
01:45:12,220 --> 01:45:13,220
the company. He wanted to make an instant
movie camera, and he wouldn't listen to any

1323
01:45:13,220 --> 01:45:14,220
critics. When it was ready, it wasn't a success.
It made only a few minutes of video, while

1324
01:45:14,220 --> 01:45:15,220
competitors already had cameras that could
make several hours. The company lost 600 million

1325
01:45:15,220 --> 01:45:16,220
dollars, and Land lost his job.

1326
01:45:16,220 --> 01:45:17,220
Land was not alone in the way he behaved.
Research shows that the worse a company does,

1327
01:45:17,220 --> 01:45:18,220
the more the bosses get advice only from the
people who agree with them. But this is the

1328
01:45:18,220 --> 01:45:19,220
opposite of what they should do; different
opinions are useful even when they are wrong.

1329
01:45:19,220 --> 01:45:20,220
The evidence suggests that it isn't social
links that create groupthink, but too much

1330
01:45:20,220 --> 01:45:21,220
confidence. Polaroid had too much confidence
that customers would always want printed pictures,

1331
01:45:21,220 --> 01:45:22,220
and they refused to look at other original
ideas. So how can you build a strong culture

1332
01:45:22,220 --> 01:45:23,220
that welcomes disagreement?

1333
01:45:23,220 --> 01:45:24,220
Think differently

1334
01:45:24,220 --> 01:45:25,220
When I asked entrepreneurs and students about
the strongest culture they had ever met in

1335
01:45:25,220 --> 01:45:26,220
an organization, the winner was Bridgewater
Associates. This company in Connecticut manages

1336
01:45:26,220 --> 01:45:27,220
over 170 billion dollars for governments,
universities, and other organizations. The

1337
01:45:27,220 --> 01:45:28,220
company culture is explained in a book of
200 key ideas. Although the company manages

1338
01:45:28,220 --> 01:45:29,220
money, none of these ideas are about money.
They are about how to behave in any situation

1339
01:45:29,220 --> 01:45:30,220
that you meet at work or outside.

1340
01:45:30,220 --> 01:45:31,220
New employees are hired only if they fit in
with the company's ideas, and there is a camp

1341
01:45:31,220 --> 01:45:32,220
where they study and discuss them. Although
there is a lot of discussion, Bridgewater

1342
01:45:32,220 --> 01:45:33,220
is a close, friendly organization. Many employees
call it a family, and people often work there

1343
01:45:33,220 --> 01:45:34,220
for a long time.

1344
01:45:34,220 --> 01:45:35,220
Although Bridgewater has a strong commitment
culture in an industry that changes all the

1345
01:45:35,220 --> 01:45:36,220
time, it has continued to be successful for
twenty years. Its secret is that it encourages

1346
01:45:36,220 --> 01:45:37,220
original ideas.

1347
01:45:37,220 --> 01:45:38,220
If you are an investor, you can only succeed
if you think differently from everyone else.

1348
01:45:38,220 --> 01:45:39,220
Bridgewater avoids groupthink by inviting
different opinions from everyone in the company.

1349
01:45:39,220 --> 01:45:40,220
When employees share independent ideas instead
of agreeing with everyone else, there is a

1350
01:45:40,220 --> 01:45:41,220
much better chance that Bridgewater will make
decisions no one else has thought of. And

1351
01:45:41,220 --> 01:45:42,220
then there is a better chance they will be
right when the rest of the market is wrong.

1352
01:45:42,220 --> 01:45:43,220
I want to look now at the culture of the company,
which lies behind its brilliant decisions.

1353
01:45:43,220 --> 01:45:44,220
Bridgewater's success begins with the man
who started the company, Ray Dalio. He's been

1354
01:45:44,220 --> 01:45:45,220
called the Steve Jobs of investing, but employees
don't behave as though he is special. They

1355
01:45:45,220 --> 01:45:46,220
are expected to be critical of him, and employee
comments are shared across the company. One

1356
01:45:46,220 --> 01:45:47,220
of the 200 key ideas is: "No one has the right
to hold a critical opinion without speaking

1357
01:45:47,220 --> 01:45:48,220
up about it." Dalio wants people who think
independently and believes that this will

1358
01:45:48,220 --> 01:45:49,220
make the culture richer and stronger, and
better able to avoid groupthink.

1359
01:45:49,220 --> 01:45:50,220
Finding complainers

1360
01:45:50,220 --> 01:45:51,220
If you're a leader talking to your employees,
how would you complete this sentence?

1361
01:45:51,220 --> 01:45:52,220
Don't bring me-; bring me-.

1362
01:45:52,220 --> 01:45:53,220
I learned about this question from David Hofmann,
and I've presented it to thousands of groups

1363
01:45:53,220 --> 01:45:54,220
of leaders. They always shout out the same
answer: "Don't bring me problems; bring me

1364
01:45:54,220 --> 01:45:55,220
answers."

1365
01:45:55,220 --> 01:45:56,220
This seems wise. We don't want people just
to complain; when they see something wrong,

1366
01:45:56,220 --> 01:45:57,220
they should find a way to fix it. But when
it comes to groupthink this isn't always a

1367
01:45:57,220 --> 01:45:58,220
good thing. Hofmann has done a lot of research
in this area, and he found that a culture

1368
01:45:58,220 --> 01:45:59,220
that looks mainly at solving problems doesn't
encourage people to investigate. If you are

1369
01:45:59,220 --> 01:46:00,220
expected to always have an answer, you come
to meetings ready with your answers, and you

1370
01:46:00,220 --> 01:46:01,220
don't get the chance to learn from others.

1371
01:46:01,220 --> 01:46:02,220
To try to avoid this problem, Google has created
a team of "complainers" - engineers across

1372
01:46:02,220 --> 01:46:03,220
the company who are well known for recognizing
problems and saying what they really think,

1373
01:46:03,220 --> 01:46:04,220
even if it is negative. Before a major change,
managers often ask this team to give critical

1374
01:46:04,220 --> 01:46:05,220
feedback. By talking to the complainers early,
the managers get the feedback, and the complainers

1375
01:46:05,220 --> 01:46:06,220
often then become the key people to support
the change.

1376
01:46:06,220 --> 01:46:07,220
Ray Dalio, at Bridgewater, doesn't expect
employees to bring him answers. One of the

1377
01:46:07,220 --> 01:46:08,220
first things he did in the company was to
create a list of problems, which any employee

1378
01:46:08,220 --> 01:46:09,220
could add to. Getting problems noted is half
the battle against groupthink; the other half

1379
01:46:09,220 --> 01:46:10,220
is listening to the right ideas for solving
them. Bridgewater collects a group of people

1380
01:46:10,220 --> 01:46:11,220
to look at the problems, share their ideas,
find out what has gone wrong and why, and

1381
01:46:11,220 --> 01:46:12,220
suggest ways of solving the problems. It is
important that ideas are shared. As Karl Weick

1382
01:46:12,220 --> 01:46:13,220
advises, "Argue like you're right and listen
like you're wrong."

1383
01:46:13,220 --> 01:46:14,220
Critical feedback

1384
01:46:14,220 --> 01:46:15,220
Even if an organization doesn't encourage
critical feedback from its employees, there

1385
01:46:15,220 --> 01:46:16,220
may be ways of changing the culture. At Index
Group, the company CEO, Tom Gerrity, brought

1386
01:46:16,220 --> 01:46:17,220
in an expert to tell him everything he did
wrong in front of his 100 employees. By showing,

1387
01:46:17,220 --> 01:46:18,220
he was happy to get feedback, he found that
employees from across the company were more

1388
01:46:18,220 --> 01:46:19,220
likely to challenge his ideas, and to challenge
one another.

1389
01:46:19,220 --> 01:46:20,220
I've learned to do something similar in my
classroom. I collect feedback from students

1390
01:46:20,220 --> 01:46:21,220
after the first month, asking for suggestions
for improvement. I then email all the feedback

1391
01:46:21,220 --> 01:46:22,220
to the class. In the next class, I discuss
the suggestions, ask for more feedback, and

1392
01:46:22,220 --> 01:46:23,220
suggest changes. Students often say that this
helps them to feel comfortable about becoming

1393
01:46:23,220 --> 01:46:24,220
more involved in improving the class.

1394
01:46:24,220 --> 01:46:25,220
It isn't just the open culture at Bridgewater
that makes it easier for employees to challenge

1395
01:46:25,220 --> 01:46:26,220
managers. When they are new in the company,
employees are encouraged to question the company's

1396
01:46:26,220 --> 01:46:27,220
key ideas. In most companies, the employee
is busy learning the job for the first few

1397
01:46:27,220 --> 01:46:28,220
months and isn't encouraged to think about
any problems. But in fact those early days,

1398
01:46:28,220 --> 01:46:29,220
when employees have more time, and before
they see the world in the company way, are

1399
01:46:29,220 --> 01:46:30,220
a good time for them to think about improving
the culture.

1400
01:46:30,220 --> 01:46:31,220
A few years ago, I was hired by Goldman Sachs
to help them attract and keep excellent employees

1401
01:46:31,220 --> 01:46:32,220
by encouraging those employees to improve
their place of work. One thing we introduced

1402
01:46:32,220 --> 01:46:33,220
was an entry interview. Managers have meetings
to ask new employees for ideas when they start,

1403
01:46:33,220 --> 01:46:34,220
instead of waiting to ask employees what they
thought of the company when they leave. It's

1404
01:46:34,220 --> 01:46:35,220
easier to start a relationship with the door
open than to try to push open a door that

1405
01:46:35,220 --> 01:46:36,220
has already been closed.

1406
01:46:36,220 --> 01:46:37,220
Movers and shapers

1407
01:46:37,220 --> 01:46:38,220
Ray Dalio at Bridgewater is interested in
understanding people who shape the world and

1408
01:46:38,220 --> 01:46:39,220
in finding out how they are similar. He's
interviewed many originals of our time and

1409
01:46:39,220 --> 01:46:40,220
has studied originals from history like Benjamin
Franklin and Albert Einstein. Of course, all

1410
01:46:40,220 --> 01:46:41,220
of these people were enthusiastic and had
great imagination, but Dalio has three other

1411
01:46:41,220 --> 01:46:42,220
qualities on his list of similarities. First,
"shapers" are independent thinkers and rebels

1412
01:46:42,220 --> 01:46:43,220
who ask a lot of questions. Second, they are
honest critics and don't care who they are

1413
01:46:43,220 --> 01:46:44,220
talking to. And third, they are not afraid
of risk; their fear of not succeeding is greater

1414
01:46:44,220 --> 01:46:45,220
than their fear of failure. If Dalio doesn't
find a shaper to follow him, Bridgewater may

1415
01:46:45,220 --> 01:46:46,220
go the same way as Polaroid. But Dalio knows
that preventing groupthink is about more than

1416
01:46:46,220 --> 01:46:47,220
the ideas of one leader. The greatest shapers
don't stop at introducing originality into

1417
01:46:47,220 --> 01:46:48,220
the world; they create cultures that encourage
originality in others.

1418
01:46:48,220 --> 01:46:49,220
CHAPTER EIGHT
Working with emotions

1419
01:46:49,220 --> 01:46:50,220
In 2007, a man called Lewis Pugh jumped into
the Arctic Sea. The ice was not completely

1420
01:46:50,220 --> 01:46:51,220
frozen, and Pugh's plan was to be the first
person to survive a long-distance swim across

1421
01:46:51,220 --> 01:46:52,220
the North Pole. Pugh had been in the British
Special Air Service before becoming the best

1422
01:46:52,220 --> 01:46:53,220
cold-water swimmer on the planet. Two years
earlier, he had jumped off of the ice to swim

1423
01:46:53,220 --> 01:46:54,220
a kilometer in Antarctica. But he doesn't
do it just to be the best in the world; he

1424
01:46:54,220 --> 01:46:55,220
wants to make people think about climate change.

1425
01:46:55,220 --> 01:46:56,220
Before he swims, something happens to Pugh
that has never been noticed in any other human;

1426
01:46:56,220 --> 01:46:57,220
his body temperature goes up from 98.6F to
101F. When it is time to get into the freezing

1427
01:46:57,220 --> 01:46:58,220
water, his body prepares.

1428
01:46:58,220 --> 01:46:59,220
The passengers on the Titanic died in water
that was 41F. In Pugh's Antarctic swim, the

1429
01:46:59,220 --> 01:47:00,220
water had been 32F. At the North Pole, it
was less than 29F. After falling into that

1430
01:47:00,220 --> 01:47:01,220
water, a British explorer had lost fingers
in three minutes; Pugh's team estimated that

1431
01:47:01,220 --> 01:47:02,220
his swim would take twenty minutes. But a
five-minute test swim at the North Pole went

1432
01:47:02,220 --> 01:47:03,220
badly and, instead of imagining success, Pugh
began to imagine failure. If he failed, he

1433
01:47:03,220 --> 01:47:04,220
would die. He became very afraid and questioned
whether he would survive. So would it have

1434
01:47:04,220 --> 01:47:05,220
been better for him to imagine success?

1435
01:47:05,220 --> 01:47:06,220
This chapter looks at the emotional cost of
going against the crowd. In my own research

1436
01:47:06,220 --> 01:47:07,220
in a healthcare company, I tested how much
employees knew about how to manage emotions.

1437
01:47:07,220 --> 01:47:08,220
Those who showed up well in the emotion test
also spoke up more with ideas and suggestions

1438
01:47:08,220 --> 01:47:09,220
in the workplace, and their managers thought
they were better employees. They had the courage

1439
01:47:09,220 --> 01:47:10,220
to challenge, but they were also able to control
their emotions when they were doing it.

1440
01:47:10,220 --> 01:47:11,220
To understand these emotional skills, I'll
look at how Pugh got ready for the freezing

1441
01:47:11,220 --> 01:47:12,220
water, and how Martin Luther King, Jr. prepared
civil rights workers to keep calm. I'll explore

1442
01:47:12,220 --> 01:47:13,220
how one group managed to throw out a dictator,
and how a leader in technology persuaded engineers

1443
01:47:13,220 --> 01:47:14,220
to make a major change to their product. By
studying how to manage emotions, you'll discover

1444
01:47:14,220 --> 01:47:15,220
whether it's better to plan for success or
failure, whether calming yourself down can

1445
01:47:15,220 --> 01:47:16,220
light fear, how to deal with your anger, and
what it takes to keep going when everything

1446
01:47:16,220 --> 01:47:17,220
seems to be against you.

1447
01:47:17,220 --> 01:47:18,220
Optimism and pessimism

1448
01:47:18,220 --> 01:47:19,220
Although many originals seem to be confident
on the outside, inside they often worry and

1449
01:47:19,220 --> 01:47:20,220
doubt their own abilities. When United States
government leaders described their most difficult

1450
01:47:20,220 --> 01:47:21,220
decisions, they didn't talk about difficult
problems but about choices that needed courage.

1451
01:47:21,220 --> 01:47:22,220
And research by Scott Sonenshein has shown
that people working for a better environment

1452
01:47:22,220 --> 01:47:23,220
are often uncertain about whether they can
succeed. Challenging the present situation

1453
01:47:23,220 --> 01:47:24,220
is often hard work, and there will be problems
and failures along the way.

1454
01:47:24,220 --> 01:47:25,220
Psychologist Julie Norem studies two different
ways of managing these challenges: optimism

1455
01:47:25,220 --> 01:47:26,220
and pessimism. Optimists expect that the best
will happen; they stay calm and expect to

1456
01:47:26,220 --> 01:47:27,220
succeed. Pessimists expect the worst; they
worry, and they imagine all the things that

1457
01:47:27,220 --> 01:47:28,220
can go wrong.

1458
01:47:28,220 --> 01:47:29,220
Most people think it's better to be an optimist
than a pessimist. Yet Norem found that, although

1459
01:47:29,220 --> 01:47:30,220
pessimists worry more and are less confident,
they do their jobs as well as the optimists.

1460
01:47:30,220 --> 01:47:31,220
And Norem soon realized that pessimists did
well because of their pessimism.

1461
01:47:31,220 --> 01:47:32,220
Norem explains that pessimism works as a way
of managing fear and worry. When pessimists

1462
01:47:32,220 --> 01:47:33,220
start to doubt themselves, they don't allow
themselves to freeze with fear. They imagine

1463
01:47:33,220 --> 01:47:34,220
an enormous failure to make them worry more,
and that gives them reasons to succeed. Once

1464
01:47:34,220 --> 01:47:35,220
they have imagined everything that can go
wrong, they look at how to avoid those problems,

1465
01:47:35,220 --> 01:47:36,220
and this makes them feel they can control
things. They worry most before they act, so

1466
01:47:36,220 --> 01:47:37,220
when they start to move they are ready to
succeed. They are confident because they know

1467
01:47:37,220 --> 01:47:38,220
they have prepared as well as possible. If
they don't worry, then they relax and don't

1468
01:47:38,220 --> 01:47:39,220
plan. It's important that pessimists don't
feel comfortable.

1469
01:47:39,220 --> 01:47:40,220
Lewis Pugh was usually an optimist. He took
risks when other people would give up. But

1470
01:47:40,220 --> 01:47:41,220
in the weeks before a major swim he was often
more of a pessimist. It was not the words

1471
01:47:41,220 --> 01:47:42,220
of his own team that encouraged him, but the
words of people who doubted him. Two years

1472
01:47:42,220 --> 01:47:43,220
earlier, before another freezing swim, an
expert had told him that it was impossible

1473
01:47:43,220 --> 01:47:44,220
and that he would die.

1474
01:47:44,220 --> 01:47:45,220
As Pugh stood shaking at the North Pole, his
pessimism told him that things were not going

1475
01:47:45,220 --> 01:47:46,220
to go well. But, instead of trying to find
reasons to be happier, he started to think

1476
01:47:46,220 --> 01:47:47,220
about every possible risk. He made plans to
be sure that he spent very little time on

1477
01:47:47,220 --> 01:47:48,220
the ice before the swim and to get to the
boat as quickly as possible afterward. "The

1478
01:47:48,220 --> 01:47:49,220
trick is to make fear your friend," he says
on his website (www.lewispugh.com). But this

1479
01:47:49,220 --> 01:47:50,220
isn't enough. Pessimism can be helpful when
you're sure about what you want to do. But,

1480
01:47:50,220 --> 01:47:51,220
when you're not so sure, doubt can get in
the way.

1481
01:47:51,220 --> 01:47:52,220
Keep believing

1482
01:47:52,220 --> 01:47:53,220
When most people list the things that frighten
them, one thing comes up very often: speaking

1483
01:47:53,220 --> 01:47:54,220
in public. If we want to understand how people
manage fear, we can just put them on stage.

1484
01:47:54,220 --> 01:47:55,220
Alison Wood Brooks asked college students
to give a speech about why they would be good

1485
01:47:55,220 --> 01:47:56,220
to work with. The speeches were filmed, and
a group of students was ready to watch them

1486
01:47:56,220 --> 01:47:57,220
and score them. With only two minutes to prepare,
many of the students were actually shaking.

1487
01:47:57,220 --> 01:47:58,220
If you were in this situation, how would you
manage your fear? When 300 professional workers

1488
01:47:58,220 --> 01:47:59,220
were asked, 90 percent suggested, "Try to
relax and calm down." But this is not the

1489
01:47:59,220 --> 01:48:00,220
best advice.

1490
01:48:00,220 --> 01:48:01,220
Before the college students gave their speeches,
Brooks asked them to say three words out loud.

1491
01:48:01,220 --> 01:48:02,220
Half of them were asked to say, "I am calm."
The other half were asked to say, "I am excited."

1492
01:48:02,220 --> 01:48:03,220
Changing one word was enough to change the
quality of the speeches. When students attached

1493
01:48:03,220 --> 01:48:04,220
the label "excited" to their emotions, they
were scored as 17 percent better at persuading

1494
01:48:04,220 --> 01:48:05,220
and 15 percent more confident than those students
who said they were "calm". The excited students

1495
01:48:05,220 --> 01:48:06,220
also gave longer speeches than the calm students.
In another experiment, when students were

1496
01:48:06,220 --> 01:48:07,220
nervous before a math test they scored 22
percent better if they were told "Try to get

1497
01:48:07,220 --> 01:48:08,220
excited" instead of "Try to remain calm."

1498
01:48:08,220 --> 01:48:09,220
Brooks wanted to find out if it's better just
to accept worry, so she gave students another

1499
01:48:09,220 --> 01:48:10,220
frightening task. They were asked to sing
in public, and they would be scored on the

1500
01:48:10,220 --> 01:48:11,220
quality of their singing. This time, one group
wasn't asked to say anything before singing,

1501
01:48:11,220 --> 01:48:12,220
another was asked to say "I am worried," and
a third "I am excited." The group who said

1502
01:48:12,220 --> 01:48:13,220
nothing scored 69 percent; the group who said
"worried" scored only 53 percent. But the

1503
01:48:13,220 --> 01:48:14,220
group who said "excited" scored 80 percent.

1504
01:48:14,220 --> 01:48:15,220
When we are frightened, why is it better to
make ourselves excited than to try to stay

1505
01:48:15,220 --> 01:48:16,220
calm? Fear is a strong emotion; when we are
frightened, our heart gets faster. If we then

1506
01:48:16,220 --> 01:48:17,220
try to relax, it's like trying to stop a car
suddenly when it's going fast. It's better

1507
01:48:17,220 --> 01:48:18,220
to take a strong emotion and turn it into
something different but equally strong.

1508
01:48:18,220 --> 01:48:19,220
Author Susan Cain says that we have a stop
system and a go system. When we haven't decided

1509
01:48:19,220 --> 01:48:20,220
what we are going to do, pessimism is dangerous.
Thinking too much about the dangers makes

1510
01:48:20,220 --> 01:48:21,220
us worry and "stop." Being optimistic makes
us more likely to do something-to "go." However,

1511
01:48:21,220 --> 01:48:22,220
in a situation where we have already decided
what we are going to do, and start to worry

1512
01:48:22,220 --> 01:48:23,220
about it, it is better to be a pessimist and
turn our worries into positive emotions like

1513
01:48:23,220 --> 01:48:24,220
excitement. This switches on our go system.

1514
01:48:24,220 --> 01:48:25,220
In previous cold-water swims, Lewis Pugh was
certain he would succeed, so being a pessimist

1515
01:48:25,220 --> 01:48:26,220
was helpful: looking at all the possible dangers
made him ready for anything. At the North

1516
01:48:26,220 --> 01:48:27,220
Pole, this worked at first, but after the
five-minute test swim, which went badly, he

1517
01:48:27,220 --> 01:48:28,220
started to worry: "What I felt on that stupid
test swim wasn't like anything I'd felt before.

1518
01:48:28,220 --> 01:48:29,220
I don't believe I can do this."

1519
01:48:29,220 --> 01:48:30,220
It was time to move away from pessimism. A
friend gave him three ideas to get excited.

1520
01:48:30,220 --> 01:48:31,220
First, he reminded Pugh that twenty-nine people
from ten countries had helped him, and he

1521
01:48:31,220 --> 01:48:32,220
put flags from those countries along the water.
Second, the friend told him to think of his

1522
01:48:32,220 --> 01:48:33,220
parents and how they had helped him. And third,
he told him to think about climate change

1523
01:48:33,220 --> 01:48:34,220
and how the swim might help. After listening
to his friend, Pugh was ready to do the swim.

1524
01:48:34,220 --> 01:48:35,220
He jumped into the freezing water and Finished,
successfully, in eighteen minutes and fifty

1525
01:48:35,220 --> 01:48:36,220
seconds.

1526
01:48:36,220 --> 01:48:37,220
For Pugh, the most difficult thing was managing
his own emotions. But other originals have

1527
01:48:37,220 --> 01:48:38,220
to manage other people's emotions. When others
are afraid to act, how can we encourage them?

1528
01:48:38,220 --> 01:48:39,220
In 2009, fifteen young tourists visited Belgrade,
the capital of Serbia. After walking them

1529
01:48:39,220 --> 01:48:40,220
around part of the city, their guide, a Serbian
in his thirties, talked about the country's

1530
01:48:40,220 --> 01:48:41,220
recent history of high potato prices and free
concerts. But they weren't ordinary tourists,

1531
01:48:41,220 --> 01:48:42,220
and they were getting impatient. They had
come to Belgrade to learn how to get rid of

1532
01:48:42,220 --> 01:48:43,220
their own country's dictator.

1533
01:48:43,220 --> 01:48:44,220
They asked the guide how the people of Serbia
had removed the Serbian dictator Slobodan

1534
01:48:44,220 --> 01:48:45,220
Milosevic. You don't need to take big risks,
the guide told them. You can do lots of little

1535
01:48:45,220 --> 01:48:46,220
things - drive more slowly than usual, push
televisions through the streets, or turn lights

1536
01:48:46,220 --> 01:48:47,220
on and off. The tourists just laughed. Small
things like that would never work for us,

1537
01:48:47,220 --> 01:48:48,220
they said. If we did that, we would be arrested
and then disappear. How can we have a revolution

1538
01:48:48,220 --> 01:48:49,220
when we can't meet in groups of more than
three?

1539
01:48:49,220 --> 01:48:50,220
They didn't know it, but the guide had heard
all this before - from Georgians in 2003,

1540
01:48:50,220 --> 01:48:51,220
from Ukrainians in 2004, from Lebanese in
2005, and from Maldivians in 2008. In each

1541
01:48:51,220 --> 01:48:52,220
case, they had gone back to their countries
and removed a dictator. The guide, Srda Popovic,

1542
01:48:52,220 --> 01:48:53,220
had taught them all. He was one of the people
behind Otpor!, the non-violent organization

1543
01:48:53,220 --> 01:48:54,220
of young people who had helped remove Milosevic.
Popovic had been attacked by the dictator's

1544
01:48:54,220 --> 01:48:55,220
police and had spent time in jail.

1545
01:48:55,220 --> 01:48:56,220
When psychologist Dan McAdams and his team
asked adults to tell them their life stories,

1546
01:48:56,220 --> 01:48:57,220
and how they felt at different times, they
saw two patterns. Some people had mostly good

1547
01:48:57,220 --> 01:48:58,220
experiences and were fairly happy during most
of their lives. But people who had found original

1548
01:48:58,220 --> 01:48:59,220
ways of helping others often had stories that
started badly when they were young but got

1549
01:48:59,220 --> 01:49:00,220
better later. Although they had more bad experiences
than the other group, these originals had

1550
01:49:00,220 --> 01:49:01,220
more happiness. They managed their problems,
and in the end, their lives were happier and

1551
01:49:01,220 --> 01:49:02,220
fuller.

1552
01:49:02,220 --> 01:49:03,220
After leading the group that removed their
dictator, Popovic began to help other groups

1553
01:49:03,220 --> 01:49:04,220
that were trying to remove dictators without
violence. Not every group succeeded, but we

1554
01:49:04,220 --> 01:49:05,220
can learn a lot from Popovic's way of managing
emotions.

1555
01:49:05,220 --> 01:49:06,220
Using users to excite teams

1556
01:49:06,220 --> 01:49:07,220
When Josh Silverman took over at Skype in
February 2008, the company had problems. Skype,

1557
01:49:07,220 --> 01:49:08,220
a leader in free computer-to-computer calls,
was no longer growing as fast as before. Silverman

1558
01:49:08,220 --> 01:49:09,220
decided he had to do something big. In April,
he announced that Skype 4.0 would appear before

1559
01:49:09,220 --> 01:49:10,220
the end of the year, and it would include
full-screen video. Most employees were deeply

1560
01:49:10,220 --> 01:49:11,220
negative about this. They thought there wasn't
enough time; the video quality would be poor;

1561
01:49:11,220 --> 01:49:12,220
and users would hate using a full screen.

1562
01:49:12,220 --> 01:49:13,220
Silverman didn't try to calm them down but
decided he needed to get them excited about

1563
01:49:13,220 --> 01:49:14,220
video. He talked to employees about the big
idea: "It's not about making cheap phone calls.

1564
01:49:14,220 --> 01:49:15,220
It's about being together when you're not
in the same room." Silverman talked about

1565
01:49:15,220 --> 01:49:16,220
how Skype allowed his children to keep close
contact with their grandparents, who were

1566
01:49:16,220 --> 01:49:17,220
thousands of miles away. Then he let other
Skype users talk about what Skype had done

1567
01:49:17,220 --> 01:49:18,220
for them. A married couple talked about how
Skype kept them together when they had to

1568
01:49:18,220 --> 01:49:19,220
spend a year living apart. A man in the army
talked about how he could be with his children

1569
01:49:19,220 --> 01:49:20,220
even when he was in another country; they
even opened Christmas presents together.

1570
01:49:20,220 --> 01:49:21,220
As they began to understand that Skype was
about connecting people, the team's worries

1571
01:49:21,220 --> 01:49:22,220
turned to excitement. Their go system was
switched on. Skype 4.0 was ready on time with

1572
01:49:22,220 --> 01:49:23,220
high-quality full-screen video calls. Soon,
Skype was adding 380,000 new users every day.

1573
01:49:23,220 --> 01:49:24,220
Less than three years later, Microsoft bought
Skype for 8.5 billion dollars; the company

1574
01:49:24,220 --> 01:49:25,220
had increased in value by 300 percent.

1575
01:49:25,220 --> 01:49:26,220
In Serbia, Popovic knew he had to show people
something to encourage them to act. People

1576
01:49:26,220 --> 01:49:27,220
were too afraid to listen, so Popovic used
a picture of a fist to encourage people's

1577
01:49:27,220 --> 01:49:28,220
go system.

1578
01:49:28,220 --> 01:49:29,220
Strength in numbers

1579
01:49:29,220 --> 01:49:30,220
If you are the only person with an idea, it
can be hard to defend it. But people can get

1580
01:49:30,220 --> 01:49:31,220
strength from just a small number of people
who think like them. To feel that you're not

1581
01:49:31,220 --> 01:49:32,220
alone, you don't need a whole crowd. Research
by Sigal Barsade and Hakan Ozcelik has shown

1582
01:49:32,220 --> 01:49:33,220
that, in business or government, even having
one friend may be enough.

1583
01:49:33,220 --> 01:49:34,220
If you want people to take risks, you have
to show them they aren't alone. This was the

1584
01:49:34,220 --> 01:49:35,220
first part of Otpor!'s success. In 1998, they
painted a fist on buildings all around Belgrade,

1585
01:49:35,220 --> 01:49:36,220
together with sentences like "I am against
the government because I love Serbia," "Bite

1586
01:49:36,220 --> 01:49:37,220
the system," and "Argue until we win." Before
they saw the fist, people who were against

1587
01:49:37,220 --> 01:49:38,220
Milosevic were afraid to say what they thought.
But, when they saw it, they realized there

1588
01:49:38,220 --> 01:49:39,220
were others who were happy to take a risk.
Later, when police arrested members of Otpor!,

1589
01:49:39,220 --> 01:49:40,220
those members were often asked who was their
leader. Popovic and his friends taught them

1590
01:49:40,220 --> 01:49:41,220
to answer, "I am one of the 20,000 leaders
of Otpor!"

1591
01:49:41,220 --> 01:49:42,220
Around the world, different organizations
have used small actions to show they are part

1592
01:49:42,220 --> 01:49:43,220
of a larger group. In Chile, to complain about
the dictator Pinochet, people turned their

1593
01:49:43,220 --> 01:49:44,220
lights on and off. When people saw their neighbors
doing that, they weren't afraid to do the

1594
01:49:44,220 --> 01:49:45,220
same. Then people were invited to drive slowly.
Taxi drivers slowed down, and so did bus drivers.

1595
01:49:45,220 --> 01:49:46,220
Soon people were walking slowly in the streets.
People understood there was no risk: it's

1596
01:49:46,220 --> 01:49:47,220
not against the law to drive or walk slowly.

1597
01:49:47,220 --> 01:49:48,220
In Poland, when people were unhappy about
government news on televisions, they knew

1598
01:49:48,220 --> 01:49:49,220
that just turning off the television wasn't
enough. So they took their televisions outside

1599
01:49:49,220 --> 01:49:50,220
and pushed them through the streets. It's
not against the law to push your television

1600
01:49:50,220 --> 01:49:51,220
through the streets.

1601
01:49:51,220 --> 01:49:52,220
In Serbia, Otpor! Found a clever way to change
people's fear to excitement: comedy. They

1602
01:49:52,220 --> 01:49:53,220
sent birthday presents to Milosevic: a ticket
out of the country, and a prison uniform.

1603
01:49:53,220 --> 01:49:54,220
It's hard to be afraid of speaking up against
a dictator when you are laughing at him.

1604
01:49:54,220 --> 01:49:55,220
Laughter can work in other situations where
people are afraid, too. When you have no power,

1605
01:49:55,220 --> 01:49:56,220
laughter is a powerful way to change strong
negative emotions into positive ones. After

1606
01:49:56,220 --> 01:49:57,220
hearing Popovic's story, a group of students
wanted to do something about the very high

1607
01:49:57,220 --> 01:49:58,220
cost of lessons at their university. They
decided to show the university president pictures

1608
01:49:58,220 --> 01:49:59,220
of their cheap and simple meals and invite
themselves to dinner at his house.

1609
01:49:59,220 --> 01:50:00,220
But Popovic also has a message that isn't
funny at all. At first, Popovic seems to be

1610
01:50:00,220 --> 01:50:01,220
an optimist. When others were ready to give
up, he thought there was a better future for

1611
01:50:01,220 --> 01:50:02,220
Serbia. But when I asked him if he was ever
unsure, he told me he had doubts for all of

1612
01:50:02,220 --> 01:50:03,220
those ten years. Even today, he worries about
the people who died, and he feels responsible.

1613
01:50:03,220 --> 01:50:04,220
The importance of now

1614
01:50:04,220 --> 01:50:05,220
On New Year's Eve in 2000, Popovic and his
friends organized a celebration in the main

1615
01:50:05,220 --> 01:50:06,220
square in Belgrade, with music and dancing.
At midnight, the famous band the Red Hot Chili

1616
01:50:06,220 --> 01:50:07,220
Peppers would appear, and everyone was very
excited. One minute before midnight, the square

1617
01:50:07,220 --> 01:50:08,220
went dark and people began counting down.
But when it was midnight, no famous band appeared.

1618
01:50:08,220 --> 01:50:09,220
Instead, a voice said, "We have nothing to
celebrate. This has been a year of war. But

1619
01:50:09,220 --> 01:50:10,220
it doesn't have to be that way. Let's make
the coming year count. Because 2000 is the

1620
01:50:10,220 --> 01:50:11,220
year."

1621
01:50:11,220 --> 01:50:12,220
When John Kotter studied 100 companies that
were trying to make major changes, he discovered

1622
01:50:12,220 --> 01:50:13,220
that the first mistake they made was to fail
to make people understand that acting quickly

1623
01:50:13,220 --> 01:50:14,220
was important. Kotter noted that managers
didn't realize how difficult it was to persuade

1624
01:50:14,220 --> 01:50:15,220
people that change needed to happen, and it
needed to happen now. If they don't understand

1625
01:50:15,220 --> 01:50:16,220
the importance of speed, employees sit back
and refuse to change. Otpor! Made people in

1626
01:50:16,220 --> 01:50:17,220
Serbia understand the importance of speed
when they announced: "This is the year."

1627
01:50:17,220 --> 01:50:18,220
To understand this more, let's look at another
piece of research by Amos Tversky and Daniel

1628
01:50:18,220 --> 01:50:19,220
Kahneman. Imagine you are the manager of a
car company. Sales are down, and you need

1629
01:50:19,220 --> 01:50:20,220
to close three factories and lose 6,000 employees.
You can choose between two different plans.

1630
01:50:20,220 --> 01:50:21,220
Plan A will save one of the three factories
and 2,000 jobs. Plan B has a one-third chance

1631
01:50:21,220 --> 01:50:22,220
of saving all three factories and 6.000 jobs,
but a two-thirds chance of saving no factories

1632
01:50:22,220 --> 01:50:23,220
and no jobs.

1633
01:50:23,220 --> 01:50:24,220
Most people, 80 percent, prefer Plan A.

1634
01:50:24,220 --> 01:50:25,220
But let's now look at the choice in a different
way.

1635
01:50:25,220 --> 01:50:26,220
Plan A will lose two factories and 4,000 jobs.

1636
01:50:26,220 --> 01:50:27,220
Plan B has a two-thirds chance of losing all
three factories and 6.000 jobs, but a one-third

1637
01:50:27,220 --> 01:50:28,220
chance of losing no factories or jobs.

1638
01:50:28,220 --> 01:50:29,220
These are the same choices as the first time,
but they don't feel like it. In this case,

1639
01:50:29,220 --> 01:50:30,220
82 percent of people prefer Plan B.

1640
01:50:30,220 --> 01:50:31,220
In the first case, the choices show what we
could gain. We prefer Plan A because it looks

1641
01:50:31,220 --> 01:50:32,220
less risky. When we are sure we will gain
something, we want to keep and protect it.

1642
01:50:32,220 --> 01:50:33,220
We want to save 2,000 jobs, rather than take
a risk and save no jobs. In the second case,

1643
01:50:33,220 --> 01:50:34,220
we are told what we are going to lose. Now
we want to avoid losing anything, even if

1644
01:50:34,220 --> 01:50:35,220
it means taking a bigger risk. We're going
to lose thousands of jobs anyway, so we decide

1645
01:50:35,220 --> 01:50:36,220
to take a big risk and hope that we lose nothing.

1646
01:50:36,220 --> 01:50:37,220
If we want people to change, is it better
to show them why it is helpful to change,

1647
01:50:37,220 --> 01:50:38,220
or the costs of not changing? According to
Peter Salovey, it depends on whether people

1648
01:50:38,220 --> 01:50:39,220
think the change is safe or risky. If they
think it is safe, it is better to talk about

1649
01:50:39,220 --> 01:50:40,220
the good things that will happen if they do
it. They will want to act immediately and

1650
01:50:40,220 --> 01:50:41,220
get there quickly. But if they think it's
risky, that doesn't work. They are comfortable

1651
01:50:41,220 --> 01:50:42,220
where they are, so they don't see why they
should change. If we want them to change,

1652
01:50:42,220 --> 01:50:43,220
we have to talk about the bad things that
will happen if they don't change. It's easier

1653
01:50:43,220 --> 01:50:44,220
for people to take a risk when they know they
will definitely lose something if they don't.

1654
01:50:44,220 --> 01:50:45,220
At Merck, the medicine company, they wanted
managers to be more involved in making changes.

1655
01:50:45,220 --> 01:50:46,220
Managers were asked to think of ideas that
would put Merck out of business. They imagined

1656
01:50:46,220 --> 01:50:47,220
that they were one of Merck's competitors
and developed ideas for new medicines that

1657
01:50:47,220 --> 01:50:48,220
were better than Merck's, or looked at markets
Merck had missed. Then they had to find ways

1658
01:50:48,220 --> 01:50:49,220
to defend the company against these competitors.

1659
01:50:49,220 --> 01:50:50,220
This "kill the company" exercise is strong
because it asks people to think about what

1660
01:50:50,220 --> 01:50:51,220
they might lose. Before, when managers thought
about new products, they didn't want to take

1661
01:50:51,220 --> 01:50:52,220
risks. But when they thought about their competitors
they realized it was a risk not to innovate.

1662
01:50:52,220 --> 01:50:53,220
Popovic realized that strong emotions were
needed to change the situation in Serbia.

1663
01:50:53,220 --> 01:50:54,220
By stopping the concert and sending people
home on New Year's Eve, he was reminding them

1664
01:50:54,220 --> 01:50:55,220
to act now.

1665
01:50:55,220 --> 01:50:56,220
Deep and surface acting

1666
01:50:56,220 --> 01:50:57,220
Anger is a good way to get people to do something.
We feel we have to fight when someone has

1667
01:50:57,220 --> 01:50:58,220
done the wrong thing. But, although anger
can encourage people to speak and to act,

1668
01:50:58,220 --> 01:50:59,220
it can also make them do it the wrong way.
Debra Meyerson and Maureen Scully suggest

1669
01:50:59,220 --> 01:51:00,220
that the key is to be hotheaded and cool-headed
at the same time. The heat pushes us toward

1670
01:51:00,220 --> 01:51:01,220
action and change; the coolness gives the
action a useful shape.

1671
01:51:01,220 --> 01:51:02,220
Arlie Hochschild has suggested that if you
are feeling a strong emotion like worry or

1672
01:51:02,220 --> 01:51:03,220
anger there are two ways to manage it: surface
acting and deep acting. Surface acting means

1673
01:51:03,220 --> 01:51:04,220
changing your face, speech, and actions to
show you are calm. If you are working for

1674
01:51:04,220 --> 01:51:05,220
an airline and an angry passenger starts to
shout at you on a plane, you may smile and

1675
01:51:05,220 --> 01:51:06,220
try to show some warmth. You change on the
outside, but inside you haven't changed. You

1676
01:51:06,220 --> 01:51:07,220
are angry with the passenger, and the passenger
probably knows it. But if you are deep acting

1677
01:51:07,220 --> 01:51:08,220
you might imagine that the passenger is under
stress, is afraid of flying, or has problems

1678
01:51:08,220 --> 01:51:09,220
at home. You feel sorry for the passenger,
and your smile is warmer.

1679
01:51:09,220 --> 01:51:10,220
Before Lewis Pugh starts out on one of his
swims, he uses deep acting. He listens to

1680
01:51:10,220 --> 01:51:11,220
music and remembers jumping from a plane in
his army days. He is returning to the excitement

1681
01:51:11,220 --> 01:51:12,220
that he felt then, and which he wants to find
again. Deep acting is a better way of managing

1682
01:51:12,220 --> 01:51:13,220
emotions than surface acting. If we want to
show our emotions, we have to feel them.

1683
01:51:13,220 --> 01:51:14,220
The dangers of venting

1684
01:51:14,220 --> 01:51:15,220
Less than a year after Rosa Parks refused
to give up her seat on a bus in Montgomery,

1685
01:51:15,220 --> 01:51:16,220
a United States court decided that separating
black and white people was against the law.

1686
01:51:16,220 --> 01:51:17,220
Now that black people could sit anywhere on
a bus, Martin Luther King, Jr. and others

1687
01:51:17,220 --> 01:51:18,220
realized they needed to help black people
reply to the violence that they might meet.

1688
01:51:18,220 --> 01:51:19,220
The team put chairs in rows, like a bus, and
asked audience members to play "black" or

1689
01:51:19,220 --> 01:51:20,220
"white" passengers. The "white" passengers
called the "black" passengers names, pushed

1690
01:51:20,220 --> 01:51:21,220
them, and threw things at them. The "black"
passengers needed to act deeply. King wanted

1691
01:51:21,220 --> 01:51:22,220
them to be angry enough to speak out, but
not to be so angry that they became violent.

1692
01:51:22,220 --> 01:51:23,220
What would be the best way to manage their
anger? Many people suggest that venting works

1693
01:51:23,220 --> 01:51:24,220
best, turning the anger against something
else like hitting a pillow, or screaming.

1694
01:51:24,220 --> 01:51:25,220
But studies have shown that venting doesn't
help, even if you think it does or it makes

1695
01:51:25,220 --> 01:51:26,220
you feel good. After venting, most people
are even angrier than before.

1696
01:51:26,220 --> 01:51:27,220
When King and his team worked on anger, they
were careful to stop people venting. Sometimes

1697
01:51:27,220 --> 01:51:28,220
a person playing a "black" man would get so
angry that he hit back. They would work with

1698
01:51:28,220 --> 01:51:29,220
him so that what he said and did was less
violent.

1699
01:51:29,220 --> 01:51:30,220
To use anger in a positive way, it is better
to avoid thinking too much about the person

1700
01:51:30,220 --> 01:51:31,220
we are angry with. It is better to think about
the people who have been hurt by the person's

1701
01:51:31,220 --> 01:51:32,220
actions. Martin Luther King, Jr. often did
this. He said he was not trying to beat the

1702
01:51:32,220 --> 01:51:33,220
white man; he wanted to free black children.
Thinking about those who have been hurt can

1703
01:51:33,220 --> 01:51:34,220
lead to a different kind of anger. Research
has shown that when we are angry with someone

1704
01:51:34,220 --> 01:51:35,220
we want to hurt them. But when we are angry
for someone we want to make things better

1705
01:51:35,220 --> 01:51:36,220
for them. We don't want to punish; we want
to help.

1706
01:51:36,220 --> 01:51:37,220
When a voice told Serbians there was nothing
to celebrate on New Year's Eve, they felt

1707
01:51:37,220 --> 01:51:38,220
an angry energy. Popovic said, "There was
an energy in the air that no rock band could

1708
01:51:38,220 --> 01:51:39,220
ever recreate. Everybody felt that they had
something important to do." The next fall

1709
01:51:39,220 --> 01:51:40,220
Milosevic lost the election, and the man who
told the people to go home became the president

1710
01:51:40,220 --> 01:51:41,220
of Serbia four years later.

1711
01:51:41,220 --> 01:51:42,220
E.B. White once wrote that he woke in the
morning unable to decide whether he wanted

1712
01:51:42,220 --> 01:51:43,220
to improve the world or to enjoy the world.
He commented in an interview with The New

1713
01:51:43,220 --> 01:51:44,220
York Times, "This makes it difficult to plan
the day."

1714
01:51:44,220 --> 01:51:45,220
As we search for happiness, many of us choose
to enjoy the world as it is. Originals take

1715
01:51:45,220 --> 01:51:46,220
a more difficult path, trying to make the
world what it could be. They may have to forget

1716
01:51:46,220 --> 01:51:47,220
about their own happiness for a time. Becoming
original is not the easiest way to find happiness,

1717
01:51:47,220 --> 01:51:48,220
but the journey brings its own happiness.

1718
